{"type":"text","timestamp":1782488687853,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"id":"prt_f049a8379001NuLpSSKSyRSD8W","messageID":"msg_f049a44d500132h7AGSIH4XLpu","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","type":"text","text":"The current inventories show the four newer mode skills have references but no assets, while `design-md-generator` is asset-heavy and example-heavy. I’m now checking the specific corpus-backed gaps against existing references so the recommendations are additions rather than duplicates.","time":{"start":1782488662905,"end":1782488687851},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_06e777fc9d85760a016a3e9e56dfec8191b8f76b146cc0e7b7","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782488687940,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_GGyM1PblTWSS6wBailnA35Si","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"AIDA|gapless|bento|two-line|2-line|hero|three dials|dials","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/pseudo-elements.md:\n  Line 225:     <motion.img layoutId=\"hero\" /> // JS-based shared element transition\n\n  Line 233:   img.style.viewTransitionName = \"hero\";\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md:\n  Line 62: Check against ALL the **DON'T** guidelines from the parent impeccable skill (already loaded in this context). Look for AI slop tells (AI color palette, gradient text, glassmorphism, hero metrics, card grids, generic fonts) and general design anti-patterns (gray on color, nested cards, bounce easing, redundant copy).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 137: - Default to the hero metric layout (big number, small label, stats, gradient) as a template. If showing real user data, a prominent metric can work, but it should display actual data, not decorative numbers.\n\n  Line 158: For variants whose topology genuinely changes (stacked vs. side-by-side, grid vs. bento), use a `steps` param whose scoped CSS branches via `:scope[data-p-structure=\"X\"]`. One structure param + one density param is a powerful combo; resist adding a third.\n\n  Line 164:   {\"value\":\"bento\",\"label\":\"Bento\"}\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/redesign-skill.md:\n  Line 43: - **Empty, flat sections with no visual depth.** Sections that are just text on a plain background feel unfinished. Add high-quality background imagery (blurred, overlaid, or masked), subtle patterns, or ambient gradients. Use reliable placeholder sources like `https://picsum.photos/seed/{name}/1920/1080` when real assets are not available. Experiment with background images behind hero sections, feature blocks, or CTAs — even a subtle full-width photo at low opacity adds presence.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/gpt-tasteskill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Elite UX/UI & Advanced GSAP Motion Engineer. Enforces Python-driven true randomization for layout variance, strict AIDA page structure, wide editorial typography (bans 6-line wraps), gapless bento grids, strict GSAP ScrollTriggers (pinning, stacking, scrubbing), inline micro-images, and massive section spacing.\n\n  Line 7: You are an elite, award-winning frontend design engineer. Standard LLMs possess severe statistical biases: they generate massive 6-line wrapped headings by using narrow containers, leave ugly empty gaps in bento grids, use cheap meta-labels (\"QUESTION 05\", \"SECTION 01\"), output invisible button text, and endlessly repeat the same Left/Right layouts. \n\n  Line 22: ## 2. AIDA STRUCTURE & SPACING\n\n  Line 24: The rest of the page MUST follow the AIDA framework:\n\n  Line 40: - **BANNED IN HERO:** Do NOT use arbitrary floating stamp/badge icons on the text. Do NOT use pill-tags under the hero. Do NOT place raw data/stats in the hero.\n\n  Line 70: 2. **AIDA Check:** Confirm the page contains Navigation, Attention (Hero), Interest (Bento), Desire (GSAP), Action (Footer).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/optimize.md:\n  Line 45:   src=\"hero.webp\"\n\n  Line 46:   srcset=\"hero-400.webp 400w, hero-800.webp 800w, hero-1200.webp 1200w\"\n\n  Line 200: - Optimize hero images\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 15: Before touching code or tweaking dials, **infer what the user actually wants**. Most LLM design output is bad because the model jumps to a default aesthetic instead of reading the room.\n\n  Line 39: Do not default to: AI-purple gradients, centered hero over dark mesh, three equal feature cards, generic glassmorphism on everything, infinite-loop micro-animations everywhere, Inter + slate-900. These are the LLM defaults. Reach past them deliberately based on the design read.\n\n  Line 45: After the design read, set three dials. Every layout, motion, and density decision below is gated by these.\n\n  Line 84: Once you have the design read (Section 0) and dials (Section 1), pick the right foundation. Do not invent CSS for things that have an official package. Do not pretend an aesthetic trend is an official system.\n\n  Line 211: * **Override:** centered hero is OK for editorial / manifesto / launch-announcement briefs where the message itself is the design.\n\n  Line 227: * **NO DUPLICATE CTA INTENT (mandatory):** Two CTAs with the same intent on one page is a Pre-Flight Fail. Examples of same intent: \"Get in touch\" + \"Contact us\" + \"Let's talk\" + \"Start a project\" + \"Start something\" + \"Reach out\" = all \"contact\" intent → pick ONE label and use it everywhere on the page (nav, hero, footer). Same for \"Try free\" + \"Get started\" + \"Sign up free\" (all \"signup\" intent) and \"View work\" + \"See selected work\" + \"Browse projects\" (all \"portfolio\" intent). One label per intent.\n\n  Line 236: * **Hero MUST fit in the initial viewport.** Headline max 2 lines on desktop, subtext max **20 words** AND max 3-4 lines, CTAs visible without scroll. If the copy is too long: reduce font scale OR cut copy. If you cannot describe the value-prop in 20 words of subtext, the value-prop is unclear, not the rule too tight. Never let the hero overflow and force scroll to find the CTA.\n\n  Line 237: * **Hero font-scale discipline.** Plan font size and image size *together*. If the hero asset is large and the headline is more than 6 words, do not start at `text-7xl/text-8xl`. Default sensible range: `text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl` for most heroes; `text-6xl md:text-7xl` only when the headline is 3-5 words. A 4-line hero headline is always a font-size error, never a copy-length error.\n\n  Line 238: * **HERO TOP PADDING CAP (mandatory):** Hero top padding max `pt-24` (≈6rem) at desktop. More than that means the hero content floats halfway down the viewport and reads as a layout bug, not as intentional space. If your hero needs more breathing room, increase font scale or asset size, not top padding.\n\n  Line 239: * **HERO STACK DISCIPLINE (max 4 text elements).** The hero is a single moment, not a feature list. Allowed text elements, max 4 in total:\n\n  Line 244:   - **BANNED in the hero:** tiny tagline below CTAs (\"Works with GitHub, GitLab, and self-hosted Git\"), trust micro-strip (\"Used by engineering teams at...\"), pricing teaser (\"Free for solo, $10/user for teams\"), feature bullet list, social-proof avatar row. All of those move to dedicated sections directly below the hero.\n\n  Line 245:   - If you have an eyebrow AND a tagline below CTAs in the same hero, drop the tagline. If you have a brand strip AND a tagline, drop the tagline. One small text element per hero, max.\n\n  Line 246: * **\"Used by\" / \"Trusted by\" logo wall belongs UNDER the hero, never inside it.** The hero is for the value prop and primary CTA. The logo wall is a separate section directly below. Do not stuff trust logos into the same flex row as the hero copy.\n\n  Line 247: * **Navigation MUST render on a single line on desktop.** If items don't fit at `lg` (1024px), condense labels, drop secondary items, or move to a hamburger. A two-line nav at desktop is broken design.\n\n  Line 250: * **BENTO CELL COUNT RULE (mandatory):** A bento grid has EXACTLY as many cells as you have content for. 3 items → 3 cells (1+2 split, or 2+1, or asymmetric trio). 5 items → 5 cells (2+3, 3+2, hero+4, etc.). If your grid has an empty cell in the middle or at the end, you planned wrong. Re-shape the grid; do not paste a blank tile.\n\n  Line 252: * **ZIGZAG ALTERNATION CAP (mandatory).** Alternating \"left-image + right-text\" then \"left-text + right-image\" zigzag layout = banal. Max 2 sections in a row with this image+text-split pattern. The 3rd consecutive image+text split is a Pre-Flight Fail. Break the pattern with a full-width section, a vertical-stack section, a bento grid, a marquee, or a different layout family.\n\n  Line 259: * **Bento Background Diversity (mandatory).** Bento and feature-grid sections cannot be 6 white-on-white cards with text inside. At least 2-3 cells in any multi-cell grid need real visual variation: a real image, a brand-appropriate gradient (not AI-purple), a pattern, a tinted background. A cream-on-cream bento with only typography inside reads as boring AI default, even when the rest of the page is good.\n\n  Line 267: 1. **Image-generation tool first.** If ANY image-gen tool is available in the environment (`generate_image`, MCP image tool, IDE-integrated gen, OpenAI image tools, etc.) you MUST use it to create section-specific assets: hero photography, product shots, texture backgrounds, mood images. Generate at the right aspect ratio for the section. Do not skip this step because hand-rolled CSS feels faster.\n\n  Line 272: 3. **Last resort: tell the user.** If neither is possible, do NOT fill the page with hand-rolled SVG illustrations or div-based \"fake screenshots.\" Instead, leave clearly-labeled placeholder slots (`<!-- TODO: hero product photo, 1600x1200 -->`) and at the end of the response say: *\"This page needs real images at: \\[list of placements\\]. Please generate or provide them.\"*\n\n  Line 274: **Even minimalist sites need real images.** A pure-text page is not minimalism. It is incomplete work. Even an editorial Linear-style site needs at least 2-3 real images (hero, one product/lifestyle shot, one supporting image). Generate B&W minimalist photography if the brief is restrained; do not skip images entirely because the dial is low.\n\n  Line 296: **Hero needs a real visual.** Text + gradient blob is not a hero - it's a placeholder.\n\n  Line 319:   - **Featured-vs-rest:** 3-4 hero specs visualised as large display tiles, the rest collapsed under a \"View full specifications\" disclosure.\n\n  Line 359: * **\"Motion claimed, motion shown.\"** If `MOTION_INTENSITY > 4`, the page must actually move: entry transitions on hero, scroll-reveal on key sections, hover physics on CTAs, at minimum. A static page that claims `MOTION_INTENSITY: 7` is broken. Conversely, if you cannot ship working motion in the available scope, drop the dial to 3 and ship a clean static page. Never half-build motion that breaks (cut-off ScrollTriggers, jumpy enters, missing cleanups).\n\n  Line 582: * **Contrast** - WCAG AA minimum for body text, AAA target for hero copy.\n\n  Line 635: * **NO version labels in the hero.** `V0.6`, `v2.0`, `BETA`, `INVITE-ONLY PREVIEW`, `EARLY ACCESS`, `ALPHA` - banned as default eyebrows. Only acceptable when the brief is explicitly about a product launch / preview status.\n\n  Line 640: * **NO `01 / 4`-style pagination on images or bento tiles.** If the user can count, they don't need the label.\n\n  Line 655: * **NO div-based fake product UI in the hero** (fake task list, fake terminal, fake dashboard built from styled divs). It is the #1 LLM-design Tell. Use a real screenshot, a generated image, a real component preview, or none at all.\n\n  Line 673: * **NO decoration text strip at hero bottom.** Patterns like `BRAND. MOTION. SPATIAL.`, `TYPE / FORM / MOTION`, `DESIGN · BUILD · SHIP`, `ESTD. 2018 · LISBON · BRAND. MOTION. SPATIAL.` as a small mono-caps strip across the bottom of the hero are an agency-portfolio cliché. Banned by default. Only acceptable when the strip carries real, navigable links (sticky bottom nav) or real status info (cookie banner, build info on a docs site).\n\n  Line 681: * **Locale / city-name / time / weather strips are banned for 99% of briefs.** \"Lisbon, working with founders\" in the hero, \"1200-690 Lisbon, Portugal\" in the footer, \"Lisbon 14:23 · 18°C\" in the nav. These are agency-portfolio decoration tells. Allowed ONLY when: the brief explicitly describes a globally-distributed studio with timezone-relevant work, OR a travel-focused brand, OR a real-world physical venue. A single contact-address mention in the footer is fine; an atmospheric locale strip is not.\n\n  Line 682: * **Scroll cues are banned.** `Scroll`, `↓ scroll`, `Scroll to explore`, `Scroll to walk through it`, animated mouse-wheel icons. If the user has not scrolled yet, they are looking at the hero. They know what scroll is. The bottom of the viewport does not need a label.\n\n  Line 799: * **Patterns to preserve** - signature interactions, recognisable hero, copy voice.\n\n  Line 844:   hero/\n\n  Line 850:     bento-grid.md\n\n  Line 866: name: asymmetric-split-hero\n\n  Line 867: category: hero\n\n  Line 872: when_to_use: \"Landing pages with one strong asset and one strong message. Default hero for SaaS, agency, premium consumer.\"\n\n  Line 892: * Blocks that depend on a design system from Section 2.A live under `blocks/<category>/<name>--<system>.md` (e.g. `feature/bento-grid--material.md`).\n\n  Line 931: - [ ] **Hero top padding**: max `pt-24` at desktop, hero content does not float halfway down the viewport?\n\n  Line 932: - [ ] **Hero stack discipline**: max 4 text elements in hero (eyebrow OR brand strip, headline, subtext, CTAs)? No tiny tagline below CTAs, no trust micro-strip in hero?\n\n  Line 938: - [ ] **Bento Background Diversity**: at least 2-3 bento cells have real visual variation (image, gradient, pattern), not all white-on-white text cards?\n\n  Line 939: - [ ] **\"Used by / Trusted by\" logo wall** lives UNDER the hero, not inside it, uses REAL SVG logos (Simple Icons / devicon) or generated SVG marks, NOT plain text wordmarks?\n\n  Line 952: - [ ] **No decoration text strip at hero bottom** (`BRAND. MOTION. SPATIAL.`)?\n\n  Line 957: - [ ] **No version labels in hero** (V0.6, BETA, INVITE-ONLY) unless the brief is a launch?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 257: - **Display version**: Headlines and hero text only - BE BOLD\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md:\n  Line 37:    - What matters most? (One hero animation vs many micro-interactions?)\n\n  Line 115: | **500–800ms** | Entrance animations | Page load, hero reveal |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/overdrive.md:\n  Line 40: Pages, hero sections, landing pages, portfolios: the \"wow\" is often sensory: a scroll-driven reveal, a shader background, a cinematic page transition, generative art that responds to the cursor.\n\n  Line 99:   .hero { animation-timeline: scroll(); }\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/minimalist-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Clean editorial-style interfaces. Warm monochrome palette, typographic contrast, flat bento grids, muted pastels. No gradients, no heavy shadows.\n\n  Line 10: Description: An advanced frontend engineering directive for generating highly refined, ultra-minimalist, \"document-style\" web interfaces analogous to top-tier workspace platforms. This protocol strictly enforces a high-contrast warm monochrome palette, bespoke typographic hierarchies, meticulous structural macro-whitespace, bento-grid layouts, and an ultra-flat component architecture with deliberate muted pastel accents. It actively rejects standard generic SaaS design trends.\n\n  Line 17: - DO NOT use primary colored backgrounds for large elements or sections (e.g., no bright blue, green, or red hero sections).\n\n  Line 74: - Background Ambient Motion: Optional. A single, very slow-moving radial gradient blob (`animation-duration: 20s+`, `opacity: 0.02-0.04`) drifting behind hero sections. Must be applied to a `position: fixed; pointer-events: none` layer. Never on scrolling containers.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/README.md:\n  Line 3: A skill for AI coding agents that generates Apple-inspired bento grid presentation cards as self-contained HTML files. No design tools needed — just describe your stats and get pixel-perfect output.\n\n  Line 40: /plugin marketplace add hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 41: /plugin install apple-bento-grid@apple-bento-grid-marketplace\n\n  Line 49: npx skills add hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 57: git clone https://github.com/hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid.git ~/.claude/skills/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 68: Use /apple-bento-grid to visualize my project stats\n\n  Line 73: Use /apple-bento-grid to visualize my startup's growth journey\n\n  Line 76: Use /apple-bento-grid to visualize my open source project achievements\n\n  Line 79: Use /apple-bento-grid to create a year-in-review card for my portfolio\n\n  Line 82: Use /apple-bento-grid to visualize our team's Q4 shipping velocity\n\n  Line 87: Create a dark theme bento grid with $2.4M revenue, 12K users, and a bar chart showing quarterly growth\n\n  Line 161: apple-bento-grid/\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/SKILL.md:\n  Line 2: name: apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 4:   Create Apple-inspired bento grid presentation cards for showcasing project stats,\n\n  Line 8:   Use when the user asks to build stat cards, bento grids, project summary cards,\n\n  Line 24: Creating visually polished presentation graphics typically requires design tools like Figma or Keynote. This skill generates Apple-quality bento grid layouts as self-contained HTML files that screenshot into pixel-perfect images — no design tool needed.\n\n  Line 28: Generate self-contained HTML files that render Apple-inspired bento card grids. Each output is a single HTML file with inline CSS — no dependencies except Google Fonts. Cards fill a tight CSS grid with minimal gaps, ready for Playwright screenshot export at 2x resolution. Both light and dark themes are available.\n\n  Line 140: Users can add their own logos or images to bento grid cards. Ask the user if they have any logos or images they'd like included.\n\n  Line 184: After generating a bento grid HTML file:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bolder.md:\n  Line 48: - **Focal point**: What should be the hero moment? (Pick ONE, make it amazing)\n\n  Line 75: - **Break the grid**: Let hero elements escape containers and cross boundaries\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/impeccable.md:\n  Line 38: - Hero / display heading ceiling: clamp() max ≤ 6rem (~96px). Above that the page is shouting, not designing. <!-- rule:skill-typo-hero-ceiling -->\n\n  Line 85:   - **Drenched**: the surface IS the color. Brand heroes, campaign pages.\n\n  Line 94: - **The hero-metric template.** Big number, small label, supporting stats, gradient accent. SaaS cliché. <!-- rule:skill-ban-hero-metric -->\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/social/launch-copy.md:\n  Line 13: npx skills add hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 33: npx skills add hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 37: github.com/hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 45: Introducing **Apple Bento Grid Skill** for Claude Code and Codex. I couldn't find a good way to present what I've been building, so I made one that generates Apple keynote-level bento grids.\n\n  Line 50: npx skills add hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 53: https://github.com/hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 77: npx skills add hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n  Line 79: https://github.com/hubeiqiao/apple-bento-grid\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"AIDA|gapless|bento|two-line|2-line|hero|three dials|dials","time":{"start":1782488687917,"end":1782488687939}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06e777fc9d85760a016a3e9e6fc1708191bee847c003dac031"}},"id":"prt_f049ae528001bAj33kKoGJvuwf","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f049a44d500132h7AGSIH4XLpu"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782488687942,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_z0jqaHbX782AdumVDe93IYDc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"Brand|Product|register|bolder|quieter","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 88 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 14: Brand: asymmetric compositions, fluid spacing with `clamp()`, intentional grid-breaking for emphasis. Rhythm through contrast: tight groupings paired with generous separations.\n\n  Line 16: Product: predictable grids, consistent densities, familiar navigation patterns. Responsive behavior is structural (collapse sidebar, responsive table), not fluid typography. Consistency IS an affordance.\n\n  Line 100: - The best hierarchy combines 2–3 dimensions at once. A heading that's larger, bolder, AND has more space above it reads as primary without trying:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/quieter.md:\n  Line 2: name: quieter\n\n  Line 14: Brand: \"quieter\" means more restrained palette, more whitespace, more typographic air. Drama is reduced, not eliminated; the POV stays intact.\n\n  Line 16: Product: \"quieter\" means reducing visual noise. Fewer background accents, flatter cards, less color, less motion. The tool should disappear more completely into the task.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 22: 5. **Brand assets that already exist** - logo, color, type, photography. For redesigns, these are starting material, not optional input (see Section 11).\n\n  Line 94: | GitHub-style devtool / community page | `@primer/css` or `@primer/react-brand` | Official Primer; Brand variant for marketing |\n\n  Line 331: * **One copy register per page.** Don't mix technical mono (\"47 tasks · 0.6 ctx-switches/day\"), editorial prose, and marketing punch in the same composition unless the brand voice explicitly calls for it.\n\n  Line 374: gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);\n\n  Line 436: gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);\n\n  Line 584: * **Brand fidelity** - primary brand color stays recognisable. Don't desaturate the brand into a dark mode.\n\n  Line 628: * **Production-Ready Cleanliness:** Code visually clean, memorable, meticulously refined.\n\n  Line 630: ### 9.F Production-Test Tells (banned outright)\n\n  Line 636: * **NO \"Brand · No. 01\"-style sub-eyebrows.** \"Marrow · No. 01 · The 6-quart\" type micro-meta lines. Skip them.\n\n  Line 667: * **NO pills/labels/tags overlaid on images.** No `<span>` overlays on photos with tags like `Brand · 02`, `PLATE · BRAND`, `Field notes - journal`. Either let the image speak alone, or add a caption directly below (outside the image).\n\n  Line 796: * **Brand tokens** - primary / accent colors, type stack, logo treatment, radii.\n\n  Line 823: * Brand itself is changing → **greenfield**.\n\n  Line 830: * Brand logo or wordmark.\n\n  Line 948: - [ ] **No pills/labels overlaid on images** (no `Plate · Brand`, no `Field notes - journal`)?\n\n  Line 1012: # Primer Brand (GitHub marketing UI)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/delight.md:\n  Line 16: Brand: delight can be distributed across copy voice, section transitions, discovery rewards, seasonal touches, personality across the whole surface.\n\n  Line 18: Product: delight at specific moments, not pages. Completion, first-time actions, error recovery, milestone crossings. Reliability and consistency carry the rest of the experience; delight pushed everywhere reads as noise.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/overdrive.md:\n  Line 77: - **`@property`** (all browsers): register custom CSS properties with types, enabling animation of gradients, colors, and complex values that CSS can't normally interpolate.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md:\n  Line 16: Brand: motion is part of the voice; one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered micro-interactions. The saturated AI default is fade-and-rise reveals on every scrolled section; that's a tell, not a choreography. Reserve scroll-triggered motion for moments that earn it.\n\n  Line 18: Product: 150–250 ms on most transitions. Motion conveys state: feedback, reveal, loading, transitions between views. No page-load choreography; users are in a task and won't wait for it.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/colorize.md:\n  Line 16: Brand: palette IS voice. Pick a color strategy first per SKILL.md (Restrained / Committed / Full palette / Drenched) and follow its dosage. Committed, Full palette, and Drenched deliberately exceed the ≤10% rule; that rule is Restrained only. Unexpected combinations are allowed; a dominant color can own the page when the chosen strategy calls for it.\n\n  Line 18: Product: semantic-first and almost always Restrained. Accent color is reserved for primary action, current selection, and state indicators. Not decoration. Every color has a consistent meaning across every screen.\n\n  Line 30:    - **Brand**: Are there existing brand colors we should use?\n\n  Line 193: | **Primary** | Brand, CTAs, key actions | 1 color, 3-5 shades |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/README.md:\n  Line 19: **Product Launch** — Light and dark themes\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/impeccable.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Use when the user wants to design, redesign, shape, critique, audit, polish, clarify, distill, harden, optimize, adapt, animate, colorize, extract, or otherwise improve a frontend interface. Covers websites, landing pages, dashboards, product UI, app shells, components, forms, settings, onboarding, and empty states. Handles UX review, visual hierarchy, information architecture, cognitive load, accessibility, performance, responsive behavior, theming, anti-patterns, typography, fonts, spacing, layout, alignment, color, motion, micro-interactions, UX copy, error states, edge cases, i18n, and reusable design systems or tokens. Also use for bland designs that need to become bolder or more delightful, loud designs that should become quieter, live browser iteration on UI elements, or ambitious visual effects that should feel technically extraordinary. Not for backend-only or non-UI tasks.\"\n\n  Line 20: 4. Read the matching register reference. **This is non-optional; skipping it produces generic output.** If the project is marketing, a landing page, a campaign, long-form content, or a portfolio (design IS the product), read `reference/brand.md`. If it is app UI, admin, a dashboard, or a tool (design SERVES the product), read `reference/product.md`. Pick by first match: (1) task cue (\"landing page\" vs \"dashboard\"); (2) surface in focus (the page, file, or route being worked on); (3) `register` field in PRODUCT.md.\n\n  Line 82:   - **Restrained**: tinted neutrals + one accent ≤10%. Product default; brand minimalism.\n\n  Line 83:   - **Committed**: one saturated color carries 30–60% of the surface. Brand default for identity-driven pages.\n\n  Line 84:   - **Full palette**: 3–4 named roles, each used deliberately. Brand campaigns; product data viz.\n\n  Line 85:   - **Drenched**: the surface IS the color. Brand heroes, campaign pages.\n\n  Line 112: If someone could look at this interface and say \"AI made that\" without doubt, it's failed. Cross-register failures are the absolute bans above. Register-specific failures live in each reference.\n\n  Line 117: - **Second-order:** if someone could guess the aesthetic family from category-plus-anti-references (\"AI workflow tool that's not SaaS-cream → editorial-typographic\", \"fintech that's not navy-and-gold → terminal-native dark mode\"), it's the trap one tier deeper. The first reflex was avoided; the second wasn't. Rework until both answers are not obvious. The brand register's [reflex-reject aesthetic lanes](reference/brand.md) list catches the currently-saturated families. <!-- rule:skill-slop-second-order-check -->\n\n  Line 131: | `bolder [target]` | Refine | Amplify safe or bland designs | [reference/bolder.md](reference/bolder.md) |\n\n  Line 132: | `quieter [target]` | Refine | Tone down aggressive or overstimulating designs | [reference/quieter.md](reference/quieter.md) |\n\n  Line 134: | `harden [target]` | Refine | Production-ready: errors, i18n, edge cases | [reference/harden.md](reference/harden.md) |\n\n  Line 159:    - Otherwise group by intent exactly as init's \"Recommend starting points\" step does (build new / improve what's there / iterate visually), tailored to `setup.register`.\n\n  Line 161:    **If `scan.targets` is non-empty, run `node {{scripts_path}}/detect.mjs --json <scan.targets joined by spaces>` once** (the bundled detector over local files: no network, no npx). `scan.via` tells you what they are: `git-changes` (the markup/style files in your dirty tree, the most relevant set), `source-dir` (e.g. `src`, `app`), `html`, or `root`. Fold the hits into your picks: many quality / contrast hits → `audit` or `polish`; a specific slop family → the matching command (gradient text or eyebrows → `quieter` / `typeset`, flat or gray palette → `colorize`, and so on). It's a real, current signal that beats guessing. If detect errors or the tree is large and slow, skip it and recommend the user run `audit` themselves; never block the suggestion on it.\n\n  Line 166: 4. **No clear command match**: general design invocation. Apply the setup steps, the General rules, and the loaded register reference, using the full argument as context.\n\n  Line 168: Setup (context gathering, register) is already loaded by then; sub-commands don't re-invoke `{{command_prefix}}impeccable`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/SKILL.md:\n  Line 149: | Standalone image card | `<img>` filling the card with `object-fit: cover; border-radius: 18px;` | Product photos |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/design-system.md:\n  Line 1132:         <span>Your Tool or Brand</span>\n\n  Line 1545:       <div class=\"label\">Product Journey</div>\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bolder.md:\n  Line 2: name: bolder\n\n  Line 8: When asked for \"bolder,\" AI defaults to the same tired tricks: cyan/purple gradients, glassmorphism, neon accents on dark backgrounds, gradient text on metrics. These are the opposite of bold. Reject them first, then increase visual impact and personality through stronger hierarchy, committed scale, and decisive type.\n\n  Line 14: Brand: \"bolder\" means distinctive. Extreme scale, unexpected color, typographic risk, committed POV.\n\n  Line 16: Product: \"bolder\" rarely means theatrics; those undermine trust. It means stronger hierarchy, clearer weight contrast, one sharper accent, more committed density. The amplification is in clarity, not drama.\n\n  Line 34:    - What's the purpose? (Marketing can be bolder than financial dashboards)\n\n  Line 36:    - What are the constraints? (Brand guidelines, accessibility, performance)\n\n  Line 118: **The test**: If you showed this to someone and said \"AI made this bolder,\" would they believe you immediately? If yes, you've failed. Bold means distinctive, not \"more AI effects.\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/design-lab.md:\n  Line 159: ### Step 1.3: Brand & Style Direction\n\n  Line 161: **Question 1: Brand Adjectives**\n\n  Line 162: - Header: \"Brand tone\"\n\n  Line 559: 1. **Card** (`.product-card`, div with \"Product Name\")\n\n  Line 814: ## Brand Tone\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md:\n  Line 238: 2. **Design intent**: If the critique found a tonal mismatch, ask whether it was intentional. For example: \"The interface feels clinical and corporate. Is that the intended tone, or should it feel warmer/bolder/more playful?\" Offer 2-3 tonal directions as options based on what would fix the issues found.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-brand-consistency/SKILL.md:\n  Line 5: # Critique Brand Consistency\n\n  Line 11: - **mood.md** — Brand personality, aesthetic keywords, visual references, do/don't examples\n\n  Line 20: - Does the overall emotional register of the screen match what the mood file prescribes?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ui-design/skills/color-system/SKILL.md:\n  Line 10: ### 1. Brand Palette\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-color/SKILL.md:\n  Line 21: - Is the overall palette warm, cool, or neutral — and is that register appropriate for the context?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/design-systems/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 442: - Brand themes: primary, sub-brands, white-label, seasonal\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/visual-critique/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 14: # Critique Brand Consistency\n\n  Line 20: - **mood.md** — Brand personality, aesthetic keywords, visual references, do/don't examples\n\n  Line 29: - Does the overall emotional register of the screen match what the mood file prescribes?\n\n  Line 191: - Buried CTA — the action is visually quieter than surrounding content\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/skills/critique-visual-hierarchy/SKILL.md:\n  Line 40: - Buried CTA — the action is visually quieter than surrounding content\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/interaction-design/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 602: ### Interactive Product Tour\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/design-ops/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 117: Review the register quarterly; update severity as the product changes.\n\n  Line 155: ### Product Metrics (mid-level)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/visual-critique/commands/critique-screen.md:\n  Line 9: 2. **Brand consistency** — Check mood, voice, and token alignment using `critique-brand-consistency` skill.\n\n  Line 22: - **Dimension**: which critique area it belongs to (Hierarchy / Brand / Composition / Typography / Colour / Affordance / Density)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-ops/skills/design-impact-reporting/SKILL.md:\n  Line 24: ### Product Metrics (mid-level)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/ui-design/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 53: ### 1. Brand Palette\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-ops/skills/design-debt-audit/SKILL.md:\n  Line 61: Review the register quarterly; update severity as the product changes.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/.gemini/extensions/ux-strategy/GEMINI.md:\n  Line 60: - Documented with examples and counter-examples for each register\n\n  Line 76: - **Brand**: voice and tone guidelines connect content strategy to brand identity\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/business-design/SKILL.md:\n  Line 38: - Emotional register — clinical, warm, playful, professional?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/ux-strategy/skills/content-strategy/SKILL.md:\n  Line 22: - Documented with examples and counter-examples for each register\n\n  Line 38: - **Brand**: voice and tone guidelines connect content strategy to brand identity\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/interaction-design/skills/onboarding-design/SKILL.md:\n  Line 30: ### Interactive Product Tour\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/design-systems/skills/theming-system/SKILL.md:\n  Line 15: - Brand themes: primary, sub-brands, white-label, seasonal\n","metadata":{"matches":88,"truncated":false},"title":"Brand|Product|register|bolder|quieter","time":{"start":1782488687911,"end":1782488687941}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06e777fc9d85760a016a3e9e6fc14c819199b48585c1bbe39b"}},"id":"prt_f049ae4ef001NUsm4KgQcOBjXN","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f049a44d500132h7AGSIH4XLpu"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782488687958,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_8ilAkLE5E5SvaLgwKWVSTR4F","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"Codex|Gemini|AI slop|slop|mock content|placeholder|layout|preflight|mechanical","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Anti-slop frontend skill for landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. The agent reads the brief, infers the right design direction, and ships interfaces that do not look templated. Real design systems when applicable, audit-first on redesigns, strict pre-flight check.\n\n  Line 45: After the design read, set three dials. Every layout, motion, and density decision below is gated by these.\n\n  Line 129:   * **INTERACTIVITY ISOLATION:** Any component using Motion, scroll listeners, or pointer physics MUST be an isolated leaf with `'use client'` at the top. Server Components render static layouts only.\n\n  Line 152: * Contain page layouts using `max-w-[1400px] mx-auto` or `max-w-7xl`.\n\n  Line 153: * **Viewport Stability:** NEVER use `h-screen` for full-height Hero sections. ALWAYS use `min-h-[100dvh]` to prevent layout jumping on mobile (iOS Safari address bar).\n\n  Line 188: * **Override:** if the brand or brief explicitly asks for purple / violet / lila, embrace it. But execute with intent: consistent palette, harmonised neutrals, restrained gradients. Not generic AI gradient slop.\n\n  Line 216: * For `VISUAL_DENSITY > 7`: generic card containers are banned. Data metrics breathe in plain layout.\n\n  Line 217: * **SHAPE CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Pick ONE corner-radius scale for the page and stick to it. Options: all-sharp (radius 0), all-soft (radius 12-16px), all-pill (full radius for interactive). Mixed systems are allowed only when there is a documented rule (e.g. \"buttons are full-pill, cards are 16px, inputs are 8px\") and that rule is followed everywhere. Round buttons in a square layout, or square cards on a pill-button page, is broken design.\n\n  Line 221: * **Loading:** Skeletal loaders matching the final layout's shape. Avoid generic circular spinners.\n\n  Line 228: * **FORM CONTRAST CHECK (mandatory, a11y):** Form inputs, placeholder text, focus rings, helper text, and error text all pass WCAG AA contrast against the section background. Light placeholders on a near-white form, white form on white page section, form labels grayer than 4.5:1 contrast → all banned. Audit every form before shipping.\n\n  Line 232: * No placeholder-as-label. Ever.\n\n  Line 238: * **HERO TOP PADDING CAP (mandatory):** Hero top padding max `pt-24` (≈6rem) at desktop. More than that means the hero content floats halfway down the viewport and reads as a layout bug, not as intentional space. If your hero needs more breathing room, increase font scale or asset size, not top padding.\n\n  Line 251: * **Section-Layout-Repetition Ban.** Once you use a layout family for a section (e.g., 3-column-image-cards, full-width-quote, split-text-image), that family can appear at most ONCE on the page. \"Selected commissions\" must not look like \"What we do.\" A landing page with 8 sections must use at least 4 different layout families.\n\n  Line 252: * **ZIGZAG ALTERNATION CAP (mandatory).** Alternating \"left-image + right-text\" then \"left-text + right-image\" zigzag layout = banal. Max 2 sections in a row with this image+text-split pattern. The 3rd consecutive image+text split is a Pre-Flight Fail. Break the pattern with a full-width section, a vertical-stack section, a bento grid, a marquee, or a different layout family.\n\n  Line 256:   - **Pre-Flight Check is mechanical:** count instances of `uppercase tracking` (or similar small-caps mono labels above headlines) across all section components. If count > ceil(sectionCount / 3), the output fails.\n\n  Line 260: * **Mobile collapse must be explicit per section.** For every multi-column layout, declare the `< 768px` fallback in the same component. No \"it'll work, Tailwind handles it\" assumptions.\n\n  Line 264: Landing pages and portfolios are **visual products**. Text-only pages with fake-screenshot divs are slop.\n\n  Line 269:    * `https://picsum.photos/seed/{descriptive-seed}/{w}/{h}` for placeholder photography (seed should describe the section, e.g. `marrow-cookware-kitchen`)\n\n  Line 272: 3. **Last resort: tell the user.** If neither is possible, do NOT fill the page with hand-rolled SVG illustrations or div-based \"fake screenshots.\" Instead, leave clearly-labeled placeholder slots (`<!-- TODO: hero product photo, 1600x1200 -->`) and at the end of the response say: *\"This page needs real images at: \\[list of placements\\]. Please generate or provide them.\"*\n\n  Line 296: **Hero needs a real visual.** Text + gradient blob is not a hero - it's a placeholder.\n\n  Line 303: * **No data-dump sections.** A 20-row publication table, a 30-row award list, a giant pricing matrix on a marketing page = wrong layout. Use:\n\n  Line 314:   A spec sheet with 10 rows + a hairline under every row is the WORST default. Either group rows into 2-3 chunks with sparse dividers, or move to a card-per-spec layout.\n\n  Line 348: * When using a design system with built-in theming (Radix Themes, shadcn/ui with `<Theme>`), set the theme ONCE in `layout.tsx` or the page root. Do not let individual sections override.\n\n  Line 361: * **MARQUEE MAX-ONE-PER-PAGE (mandatory).** Horizontal scrolling text marquees (\"logos endlessly scrolling\", \"manifesto scrolling sideways\", \"kinetic word strip\") are appropriate at most ONCE per page. Two or more marquees on the same page reads as lazy filler. Pick the one section where the marquee actually serves the content; the others get a different layout.\n\n  Line 514: * **Layout Transitions:** Use Motion's `layout` and `layoutId` props for visible state changes (re-ordering lists, expanding modals, shared elements between routes). Do not wrap static content in `layout` props \"for safety\" - it costs measurement work.\n\n  Line 557: * **8-10 (Asymmetric):** Masonry layouts, CSS Grid with fractional units (`grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr 1fr`), massive empty zones (`padding-left: 20vw`).\n\n  Line 558: * **MOBILE OVERRIDE:** For levels 4-10, asymmetric layouts above `md:` MUST collapse to strict single-column (`w-full`, `px-4`, `py-8`) on viewports `< 768px`.\n\n  Line 617: * **NO generic avatars.** No SVG \"egg\" or Lucide user icons → use believable photo placeholders or specific styling.\n\n  Line 619: * **NO startup-slop brand names.** \"Acme\", \"Nexus\", \"SmartFlow\", \"Cloudly\" → invent contextual, premium names that sound real.\n\n  Line 626: * **NO broken Unsplash links.** Use `https://picsum.photos/seed/{descriptive-string}/{w}/{h}`, or generated photo placeholders, or actual assets.\n\n  Line 677: * **NO `border-t` + `border-b` on every row of a long list / spec table.** Pick one (bottom-border between rows OR top-border above the group) and use it sparsely. A 10-row spec table with hairlines under each row is the laziest layout - see Section 4.9 for alternative UI components.\n\n  Line 768: * **Skeleton Shimmer** - Shifting light reflection across placeholders.\n\n  Line 800: * **Patterns to retire** - AI-slop tells, broken layouts, dead links, generic stock imagery, perf traps.\n\n  Line 879: 1. **Visual sketch** - short ASCII or description of the layout.\n\n  Line 926: - [ ] **Form Contrast Check**: form inputs, placeholders, focus rings, labels all pass WCAG AA against the section background?\n\n  Line 933: - [ ] **EYEBROW COUNT (mechanical)**: count instances of `uppercase tracking` micro-labels above section headlines across all components. Count ≤ ceil(sectionCount / 3)? Hero counts as 1.\n\n  Line 935: - [ ] **Zigzag Alternation Cap**: no 3+ consecutive sections with the same image+text-split layout?\n\n  Line 944: - [ ] **Section-Layout-Repetition** check: no two sections share the same layout family (at least 4 different families across 8 sections)?\n\n  Line 947: - [ ] **Real images used** (gen-tool first, then Picsum-seed, then explicit placeholder slots) - NO div-based fake screenshots, NO hand-rolled decorative SVGs, NO pure-text minimalism?\n\n  Line 968: - [ ] **Mobile collapse** explicit (`w-full`, `px-4`, `max-w-7xl mx-auto`) for high-variance layouts?\n\n  Line 1070: - https://design-system.service.gov.uk/styles/layout/\n\n  Line 1080: - https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/layout/grid/\n\n  Line 1101: - https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Guides/Grid_layout\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 10: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces that avoid generic \"AI slop\" aesthetics. Implement real working code with exceptional attention to aesthetic details and creative choices. Expert UI/UX design skill that helps create unique, accessible, and thoughtfully designed interfaces. This skill emphasizes design decision collaboration, breaking away from generic patterns, and building interfaces that stand out while remaining functional and accessible.\n\n  Line 34: - **Editorial/magazine** - strong typography hierarchy, asymmetric layouts\n\n  Line 38: - **Industrial/utilitarian** - functional, no-nonsense, mechanical precision\n\n  Line 52: - **Patterns**: Cookie-cutter layouts, predictable component arrangements\n\n  Line 152: 7. **Approval**: Have I asked before implementing colors, fonts, sizes, layouts?\n\n  Line 504: - Always add loading states, spinners, placeholder animations\n\n  Line 512: - Nest wrappers as needed for complex layouts\n\n  Line 522: - Implement CSS Grid and Flexbox for flexible layouts\n\n  Line 684: - Create cookie-cutter layouts that look AI-generated\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/ui-skills-root.md:\n  Line 16: Use it when an agent in Codex, Cursor, or Claude Code has a clear UI goal.\n\n  Line 57: For quick cleanup, prefer the most specific craft, visual, or layout skill available.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/output-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Overrides default LLM truncation behavior. Enforces complete code generation, bans placeholder patterns, and handles token-limit splits cleanly. Apply to any task requiring exhaustive, unabridged output.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/optimize.md:\n  Line 100:   const height = el.offsetHeight; // Read (forces layout)\n\n  Line 120: - Avoid casual animation of layout-driving properties (`width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, margins)\n\n  Line 217: - Avoid animations that cause layout shifts\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Semantic Design System Skill for Google Stitch. Generates agent-friendly DESIGN.md files that enforce premium, anti-generic UI standards — strict typography, calibrated color, asymmetric layouts, perpetual micro-motion, and hardware-accelerated performance.\n\n  Line 9: This skill generates `DESIGN.md` files optimized for Google Stitch screen generation. It translates the battle-tested anti-slop frontend engineering directives into Stitch's native semantic design language — descriptive, natural-language rules paired with precise values that Stitch's AI agent can interpret to produce premium, non-generic interfaces.\n\n  Line 15: - Optionally: Stitch MCP Server for programmatic integration with Cursor, Antigravity, or Gemini CLI\n\n  Line 60: - **Asymmetric Structure:** Centered Hero layouts BANNED when variance exceeds 4\n\n  Line 66: - **Cards:** Use ONLY when elevation communicates hierarchy. Tint shadows to background hue. For high-density layouts, replace cards with border-top dividers or negative space\n\n  Line 68: - **Loading States:** Skeletal loaders matching layout dimensions — no generic circular spinners\n\n  Line 77: - Contain layouts using max-width constraints (e.g., 1400px centered)\n\n  Line 82: - **Mobile-First Collapse (< 768px):** All multi-column layouts collapse to single column. No exceptions\n\n  Line 107: - No 3-column equal card layouts\n\n  Line 122: Example: \"A restrained, gallery-airy interface with confident asymmetric layouts\n\n  Line 145: * **Loaders:** Skeletal shimmer matching exact layout dimensions. No circular spinners.\n\n  Line 161: no generic placeholder names, no broken image links.)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md:\n  Line 51: Apply `-webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased` to the root layout on macOS for crisper text.\n\n  Line 55: Use `font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums` for any dynamically updating numbers to prevent layout shift.\n\n  Line 93: | Numbers cause layout shift | Apply `tabular-nums` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/overdrive.md:\n  Line 49: Charts and dashboards: the \"wow\" is in fluidity: GPU-accelerated rendering via Canvas/WebGL for massive datasets, animated transitions between data states, force-directed graph layouts that settle naturally.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/baseline.md:\n  Line 3: description: Quickly deslop UI code by fixing spacing, hierarchy, typography, and small layout issues. Use when the interface needs a fast cleanup or polish pass.\n\n  Line 8: Enforces an opinionated UI baseline to prevent AI-generated interface slop.\n\n  Line 50: - NEVER animate layout properties (`width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, `margin`, `padding`)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md:\n  Line 156: - **Grid-template-rows or FLIP-style transforms**: expanding and reflowing layout without animating `height` directly\n\n  Line 158: The hard rule isn't \"transform and opacity only.\" It's: avoid animating layout-driving properties casually (`width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, margins), keep expensive effects bounded to small or isolated areas, and verify smoothness in-browser on target viewports.\n\n  Line 161: - **Layout safety**: Avoid casual animation of layout-driving properties (`width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, margins)\n\n  Line 190: - Animate layout properties casually (`width`, `height`, `top`, `left`, margins) when transform, FLIP, or grid-based techniques would work\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/interaction-design.md:\n  Line 75: **Skeleton Screens**: Preserve layout while loading\n\n  Line 134: **Framer Motion layout animations**:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/pseudo-elements.md:\n  Line 225:     <motion.img layoutId=\"hero\" /> // JS-based shared element transition\n\n  Line 278: #### `native-placeholder-styling`\n\n  Line 279: Use ::placeholder for input placeholder styling, not wrapper elements.\n\n  Line 284:   {!value && <span className={styles.placeholder}>Enter text...</span>}\n\n  Line 291: input::placeholder {\n\n  Line 317: components/lightbox/index.tsx:45 - [transition-over-js-library] Using motion layoutId instead of View Transitions API\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/minimalist-skill.md:\n  Line 10: Description: An advanced frontend engineering directive for generating highly refined, ultra-minimalist, \"document-style\" web interfaces analogous to top-tier workspace platforms. This protocol strictly enforces a high-contrast warm monochrome palette, bespoke typographic hierarchies, meticulous structural macro-whitespace, bento-grid layouts, and an ultra-flat component architecture with deliberate muted pastel accents. It actively rejects standard generic SaaS design trends.\n\n  Line 21: - DO NOT use generic placeholder names like \"John Doe\", \"Acme Corp\", or \"Lorem Ipsum\". Use realistic, contextual content.\n\n  Line 44:   - Utilize asymmetrical CSS Grid layouts.\n\n  Line 66: - Photography: Use high-quality, desaturated images with a warm tone. Apply subtle overlays (`opacity: 0.04` warm grain) to blend photos into the monochrome palette. Never use oversaturated stock photos. Use reliable placeholders like `https://picsum.photos/seed/{context}/1200/800` when real assets are unavailable.\n\n  Line 75: - Performance: Animate exclusively via `transform` and `opacity`. No layout-triggering properties (`top`, `left`, `width`, `height`). Use `will-change: transform` sparingly and only on actively animating elements.\n\n  Line 78: When tasked with writing frontend code (HTML, React, Tailwind, Vue) or designing a layout:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/delight.md:\n  Line 253: **WARNING**: Avoid cliched loading messages like \"Herding pixels\", \"Teaching robots to dance\", \"Consulting the magic 8-ball\", \"Counting backwards from infinity\". These are AI-slop copy, instantly recognizable as machine-generated. Write messages that are specific to what your product actually does.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:\n  Line 3: description: Audit and fix animation performance issues including layout thrashing, compositor properties, scroll-linked motion, and blur effects. Use when animations stutter, transitions jank, or reviewing CSS/JS animation performance.\n\n  Line 29: - animating layout, filters, masks, gradients, or CSS variables\n\n  Line 36: - layout: size, position, flow, grid, flex\n\n  Line 56: - do not interleave layout reads and writes in the same frame\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"Codex|Gemini|AI slop|slop|mock content|placeholder|layout|preflight|mechanical","time":{"start":1782488687937,"end":1782488687956}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06e777fc9d85760a016a3e9e6fc1808191adb160f3e7eedd71"}},"id":"prt_f049ae52f0012e3A6j9Q3T16VB","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f049a44d500132h7AGSIH4XLpu"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782488688080,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_wv1n4nUVebyryOzLqPHDOukb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"gesture|interaction|micro|state|navigation|forms|form state|data visualization|data-viz","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 26: Before any code, state in one line: **\"Reading this as: \\<page kind> for \\<audience>, with a \\<vibe> language, leaning toward \\<design system or aesthetic family>.\"**\n\n  Line 39: Do not default to: AI-purple gradients, centered hero over dark mesh, three equal feature cards, generic glassmorphism on everything, infinite-loop micro-animations everywhere, Inter + slate-900. These are the LLM defaults. Reach past them deliberately based on the design read.\n\n  Line 99: | Modern SaaS where you own the components | shadcn/ui (`npx shadcn@latest add ...`) | You own the code, easy to customise; never ship default state |\n\n  Line 118: | **Apple Liquid Glass** | Apple documents this for Apple platforms only. **There is no official `liquid-glass.css`.** Web implementations are approximations using `backdrop-filter` + layered borders + highlights. Label clearly as approximation. |\n\n  Line 128:   * **RSC SAFETY:** Global state works ONLY in Client Components. In Next.js, wrap providers in a `\"use client\"` component.\n\n  Line 137: * Global state ONLY for deep prop-drilling avoidance - Zustand, Jotai, or React context.\n\n  Line 220: LLMs default to \"static successful state only.\" Always implement full cycles:\n\n  Line 223: * **Error States:** Clear, inline (forms), or contextual (toasts only for transient).\n\n  Line 244:   - **BANNED in the hero:** tiny tagline below CTAs (\"Works with GitHub, GitLab, and self-hosted Git\"), trust micro-strip (\"Used by engineering teams at...\"), pricing teaser (\"Free for solo, $10/user for teams\"), feature bullet list, social-proof avatar row. All of those move to dedicated sections directly below the hero.\n\n  Line 325:   - **Reads like an LLM trying to sound thoughtful** (passive-aggressive humility, fake-craftsman labels, mock-poetic micro-meta)\n\n  Line 360: * **MOTION MUST BE MOTIVATED (mandatory).** Before adding any animation, ask: \"what does this animation communicate?\" Valid answers: hierarchy (drawing attention to the right thing), storytelling (revealing content in sequence that matches a narrative), feedback (acknowledging a user action), state transition (showing something changed). Invalid answer: \"it looked cool\". GSAP everywhere because GSAP is available is amateur. Each ScrollTrigger, each marquee, each pinned section needs a reason. If you cannot articulate the reason in one sentence, drop the animation.\n\n  Line 512: * **Custom scroll progress calculations using `window.scrollY`** in React state. Same reason. Re-renders on every frame.\n\n  Line 513: * **`requestAnimationFrame` loops that touch React state.** Use motion values (`useMotionValue` + `useTransform`) instead.\n\n  Line 514: * **Layout Transitions:** Use Motion's `layout` and `layoutId` props for visible state changes (re-ordering lists, expanding modals, shared elements between routes). Do not wrap static content in `layout` props \"for safety\" - it costs measurement work.\n\n  Line 561: * **1-3 (Static):** No automatic animations. CSS `:hover` and `:active` states only. `prefers-reduced-motion` is the default mode anyway.\n\n  Line 627: * **shadcn/ui customization:** Allowed, but NEVER in default state. Customize radii, colors, shadows, typography to the project aesthetic.\n\n  Line 636: * **NO \"Brand · No. 01\"-style sub-eyebrows.** \"Marrow · No. 01 · The 6-quart\" type micro-meta lines. Skip them.\n\n  Line 638: **Section numbering & micro-labels**\n\n  Line 646: * **NO decorative colored status dots on every list/nav/badge.** A colored dot before \"ONE Q4 SLOT OPEN\" or before every nav link, or every task row - banned by default. Acceptable only when the dot conveys actual semantic state (a server status, an availability flag) and is used sparingly.\n\n  Line 663: * **NO micro-meta-sentences under eyebrows.** Sentences like *\"Each of these is a feature we ship today, not a roadmap promise. The list will stay short on purpose.\"* sitting under a section heading are clutter. Eyebrow + Headline + Body is enough.\n\n  Line 683: * **ZERO decorative status dots by default.** A coloured dot before nav items, before list rows, before badges, before status labels is a Tell. Only acceptable when conveying real semantic state (a live indicator on actual server status, a live availability flag) and limited to one per page section.\n\n  Line 776: * **Motion (`motion/react`)** - default for UI / Bento / state-change motion.\n\n  Line 795: Document the current state before proposing changes:\n\n  Line 799: * **Patterns to preserve** - signature interactions, recognisable hero, copy voice.\n\n  Line 808: * **Honor existing accessibility wins.** Do not regress focus states, alt text, keyboard nav, contrast.\n\n  Line 816: 4. **Motion layer** - add `MOTION_INTENSITY`-appropriate micro-interactions to existing components.\n\n  Line 858:   navigation/\n\n  Line 901: * Multi-step forms / wizards (use Form-specific patterns; this skill won't make them better).\n\n  Line 932: - [ ] **Hero stack discipline**: max 4 text elements in hero (eyebrow OR brand strip, headline, subtext, CTAs)? No tiny tagline below CTAs, no trust micro-strip in hero?\n\n  Line 933: - [ ] **EYEBROW COUNT (mechanical)**: count instances of `uppercase tracking` micro-labels above section headlines across all components. Count ≤ ceil(sectionCount / 3)? Hero counts as 1.\n\n  Line 941: - [ ] **Motion motivated**: every animation can be justified in one sentence (hierarchy / storytelling / feedback / state transition), no GSAP-for-show?\n\n  Line 951: - [ ] **No micro-meta-sentences** under eyebrows (\"Each of these is a feature we ship today...\")?\n\n  Line 959: - [ ] **No decorative dots** (zero by default, only for real semantic state)?\n\n  Line 971: - [ ] **Empty / loading / error** states provided?\n\n  Line 1041: - https://fluent2.microsoft.design/get-started/develop\n\n  Line 1042: - https://fluent2.microsoft.design/components/web/react/\n\n  Line 1043: - https://github.com/microsoft/fluentui\n\n  Line 1044: - https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/fluent-ui/web-components/\n\n  Line 1105: ### Apple Liquid Glass (Apple platforms only)\n\n  Line 1118: Apple documents Liquid Glass inside Apple's Human Interface Guidelines and Developer Documentation for **Apple platforms**. It is a dynamic material used across Apple platform UI. Apple's native implementation belongs to Apple platform APIs and system components, **not a public web CSS package**.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 33: - **Playful/toy-like** - bright colors, rounded shapes, delightful interactions\n\n  Line 91:    - Clickable: Use distinct colors, hover state changes, cursor feedback, subtle lift effects\n\n  Line 103:    - Consider every pixel, interaction, and transition\n\n  Line 134: - Subtle: Felt rather than seen (100-300ms for most interactions)\n\n  Line 176:    - Focus/hover states\n\n  Line 192: - **Interactive states**:\n\n  Line 368: For detailed motion specs, see MOTION-SPEC.md (easing curves, duration tables, state-specific animations, implementation patterns).\n\n  Line 380:      - Pinch/zoom gestures on mobile (not +/- buttons)\n\n  Line 383:    - Every interaction provides instantaneous visual feedback (within 100ms)\n\n  Line 385:      - **Visual**: Button pressed state, hover effects, color changes\n\n  Line 395:      - **Visual consistency**: All primary buttons have same colors, sizes, hover states\n\n  Line 397:      - **Interaction consistency**: All drag targets have same hover state and drop feedback\n\n  Line 398:      - **Pattern consistency**: All forms validate on blur and submit\n\n  Line 408:      - Undo/redo for all state changes\n\n  Line 411:      - Preserve user input on errors (don't clear forms)\n\n  Line 428:    Prioritize natural language interaction where appropriate:\n\n  Line 443:    - Simple forms (just use inputs)\n\n  Line 457:    - Simplified mobile navigation (hamburger menu) vs full desktop nav\n\n  Line 471: - Clear structure with intuitive navigation menus\n\n  Line 475: - Maintain navigation context (highlight current page, preserve scroll position)\n\n  Line 504: - Always add loading states, spinners, placeholder animations\n\n  Line 532: - Consider hover states for desktop, focus states for touch/keyboard\n\n  Line 556: - Provide visible focus states\n\n  Line 591: - Test keyboard navigation\n\n  Line 594: - Ensure focus states are visible\n\n  Line 599: - Verify touch interactions on mobile\n\n  Line 696: - Provide immediate feedback for interactions\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 16: Product: predictable grids, consistent densities, familiar navigation patterns. Responsive behavior is structural (collapse sidebar, responsive table), not fluid typography. Consistency IS an affordance.\n\n  Line 110: - Be aware of reading flow: in LTR languages, the eye naturally scans top-left to bottom-right, but primary action placement depends on context (e.g., bottom-right in dialogs, top in navigation).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/delight.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Add personality and memorable moments through thoughtful interaction details and emotional UX touches.\"\n\n  Line 27:    - **Success states**: Completed actions (save, send, publish)\n\n  Line 28:    - **Empty states**: First-time experiences, onboarding\n\n  Line 29:    - **Loading states**: Waiting periods that could be entertaining\n\n  Line 31:    - **Interactions**: Hover states, clicks, drags\n\n  Line 42:    - **Subtle sophistication**: Refined micro-interactions (luxury brands)\n\n  Line 69: - Respect the user's state (don't be playful during critical errors)\n\n  Line 83: ### Micro-interactions & Animation\n\n  Line 133: **Encouraging empty states**:\n\n  Line 156: - Empty state illustrations (not stock icons)\n\n  Line 157: - Error state illustrations (friendly monsters, quirky characters)\n\n  Line 158: - Loading state illustrations (animated characters)\n\n  Line 159: - Success state illustrations (celebrations)\n\n  Line 194: **Form interactions**:\n\n  Line 197: - Success state that celebrates valid input\n\n  Line 213: - Don't play on every interaction (sound fatigue is real)\n\n  Line 294: - Make every interaction delightful (special moments should be special)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/SKILL.md:\n  Line 77: | No preference stated | **Both** — generate two files, let user choose |\n\n  Line 98: | **Quote** | Mission statement, testimonial | Dark bg, white text, green `<em>` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/design-system.md:\n  Line 356:   <div class=\"hero-tagline\">statement</div>\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/README.md:\n  Line 118: | **Quote** | Mission statements | Dark background, colored emphasis |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/minimalist-skill.md:\n  Line 10: Description: An advanced frontend engineering directive for generating highly refined, ultra-minimalist, \"document-style\" web interfaces analogous to top-tier workspace platforms. This protocol strictly enforces a high-contrast warm monochrome palette, bespoke typographic hierarchies, meticulous structural macro-whitespace, bento-grid layouts, and an ultra-flat component architecture with deliberate muted pastel accents. It actively rejects standard generic SaaS design trends.\n\n  Line 51:   - Hover state should be a subtle color shift to `#333333` or a micro-scale `transform: scale(0.98)`.\n\n  Line 57:   - Use a clean, sharp `+` and `-` icon for the toggle state.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:\n  Line 27: - refactoring janky interactions or transitions\n\n  Line 30: - reviewing components that use will-change, transforms, or measurement\n\n  Line 65: - use JS-driven animation only when interaction requires it\n\n  Line 111: - use view transitions only for navigation-level changes\n\n  Line 112: - avoid view transitions for interaction-heavy UI\n\n  Line 150: - for any non-default choice, state the constraint that justifies it (surface size, duration, or interaction requirement)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/brutalist-skill.md:\n  Line 17: *   **Characteristics:** High-contrast light modes (newsprint/off-white substrates). Reliance on monolithic, heavy sans-serif typography. Unforgiving structural grids outlined by visible dividing lines. Aggressive, asymmetric use of negative space punctuated by oversized, viewport-bleeding numerals or letterforms. Heavy use of primary red as an alert/accent color.\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"gesture|interaction|micro|state|navigation|forms|form state|data visualization|data-viz","time":{"start":1782488688070,"end":1782488688079}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06e777fc9d85760a016a3e9e6fc18c81918543270837428a29"}},"id":"prt_f049ae56e0011rchnluM0iPDce","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f049a44d500132h7AGSIH4XLpu"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782488688153,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_16l69WjvONQFkMohkUYayeKO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"DESIGN\\.md|PRODUCT\\.md|stitch|author|forward|tokens|Style Reference","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 89: | Microsoft / enterprise SaaS / dashboards | `@fluentui/react-components` or `@fluentui/web-components` | Official Fluent UI, Microsoft tokens, accessibility done |\n\n  Line 90: | Google-ish UI, Material-flavored product | `@material/web` + Material 3 tokens | Official, theme-able via Material Theming |\n\n  Line 93: | Atlassian / Jira-style product | `@atlaskit/*` + `@atlaskit/tokens` | Official Atlassian DS |\n\n  Line 102: **Honesty rule:** if the brief reads as one of the systems above, install and use the **official** package. Do not recreate its CSS by hand. Do not import a system's tokens but then override 90% of them.\n\n  Line 533: * Use Tailwind `dark:` variant OR CSS variables for tokens. Pick one strategy per project.\n\n  Line 578: * **CSS variables** (for shadcn/ui, Radix Themes, or component libraries with theming): define semantic tokens (`--surface`, `--surface-elevated`, `--text-primary`, `--accent`) and swap values under `[data-theme=\"dark\"]` or `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)`.\n\n  Line 789: * **Redesign - Preserve** - modernise without breaking the brand. Audit first, extract brand tokens, evolve gradually.\n\n  Line 796: * **Brand tokens** - primary / accent colors, type stack, logo treatment, radii.\n\n  Line 967: - [ ] **Dark mode** tokens defined and tested in both modes?\n\n  Line 997: npm install @fluentui/web-components @fluentui/tokens\n\n  Line 1022: yarn add @atlaskit/css-reset @atlaskit/tokens @atlaskit/button @atlaskit/badge @atlaskit/section-message @atlaskit/card\n\n  Line 1061: - https://atlassian.design/tokens/design-tokens\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 201: - **Cool greys** (blue undertones): Modern, tech-forward, professional\n\n  Line 668:    - For: Modern, tech-forward feel\n\n  Line 718: - RESPONSIVE-DESIGN.md - Mobile-first breakpoints and patterns\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/ui-skills-root.md:\n  Line 6:   author: ibelick\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 54: - **Spacing system**: Use a consistent scale (a framework's built-in scale like Tailwind's, rem-based tokens, or a custom system). The specific values matter less than consistency.\n\n  Line 63: - Use a consistent spacing scale (framework scales like Tailwind, rem-based tokens, or a custom scale all work). What matters is that values come from a defined set, not arbitrary numbers.\n\n  Line 65: - Name tokens semantically if using custom properties: `--space-xs` through `--space-xl`, not `--spacing-8`\n\n  Line 152: Each variant MUST declare a `density` param. Drive all spacing tokens in the variant's scoped CSS through `calc(var(--p-density, 1) * <base>)`: paddings, gaps, column widths. Users slide from airy to packed and see layout re-breathe with no regeneration.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/SKILL.md:\n  Line 15:   author: Joe Hu\n\n  Line 35:    - **Read for theme**: Section 1 (light tokens) or Section 9 (dark tokens)\n\n  Line 79: See design-system.md **Section 9** for complete dark theme tokens, or **Section 1** for light theme tokens.\n\n  Line 202: - [`design-system.md`](design-system.md) — Complete design tokens (light + dark), card CSS/HTML, layout templates, and skeleton\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/design-system.md:\n  Line 3: Complete design tokens, card components, layout templates, and HTML skeleton for generating Apple-inspired bento grid presentations. Supports both light and dark themes.\n\n  Line 7: 1. [Design Tokens](#1-design-tokens) — Colors, typography, spacing (light theme)\n\n  Line 15: 9. [Dark Theme](#9-dark-theme) — Complete dark theme tokens, card overrides, and skeleton\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/README.md:\n  Line 163: ├── design-system.md      # Complete design tokens, CSS/HTML for all components\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/pseudo-elements.md:\n  Line 6:   author: raphael-salaja\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/polish.md:\n  Line 18: 1. **Find the design system**: Search for design system documentation, component libraries, style guides, or token definitions. Study the core patterns: design principles, target audience, color tokens, spacing scale, typography styles, component API, motion conventions.\n\n  Line 19: 2. **Note the conventions**: How are shared components imported? What spacing scale is used? Which colors come from tokens vs hard-coded values? What motion and interaction patterns are established? What flow shapes are used for comparable actions (modal vs full-page, inline vs route, save-on-blur vs explicit submit)?\n\n  Line 97: - **Consistent token usage**: No hard-coded colors, all use design tokens\n\n  Line 194: - [ ] Spacing uses design tokens consistently\n\n  Line 227: - Hard-code values that should use design tokens\n\n  Line 247: - **Consolidate tokens**: If you introduced new values, check whether they should be tokens.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/design-lab.md:\n  Line 76:   --color-*     /* Color tokens */\n\n  Line 77:   --spacing-*   /* Spacing tokens */\n\n  Line 78:   --font-*      /* Typography tokens */\n\n  Line 79:   --radius-*    /* Border radius tokens */\n\n  Line 375: - Use the project's existing spacing tokens—just apply them differently\n\n  Line 386: - Explore different uses of the project's existing design tokens\n\n  Line 742: - NEVER delete user-authored files\n\n  Line 798: - [Any new tokens to add]\n\n  Line 799: - [Existing tokens to use]\n\n  Line 830: - **Primary:** [color tokens]\n\n  Line 831: - **Secondary:** [color tokens]\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/morphing-icons.md:\n  Line 6:   author: raphael-salaja\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/frontend-slides.md:\n  Line 43: - Every slide is authored inside a fixed 1920×1080 stage.\n\n  Line 158: - For conservative or high-stakes decks, make the safe preset especially restrained; choose a calm, higher-formality bold template; make the wildcard either another restrained template or a custom design that feels authoritative rather than decorative.\n\n  Line 165: - Match the user's stated occasion, audience, mood/vibe, and content density. The custom design should feel authored for this deck, not merely \"stylish.\"\n\n  Line 186: - If the slide needs chrome, use real deck chrome only: the deck title, section title, date, author, company, page number, or a genuine content phrase from the user's material.\n\n  Line 299:      - Step 3: Once signed up, run `vercel login` and follow the prompts (it opens a browser window to authorize)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/stitch-skill.md:\n  Line 2: name: stitch-design-taste\n\n  Line 3: description: Semantic Design System Skill for Google Stitch. Generates agent-friendly DESIGN.md files that enforce premium, anti-generic UI standards — strict typography, calibrated color, asymmetric layouts, perpetual micro-motion, and hardware-accelerated performance.\n\n  Line 9: This skill generates `DESIGN.md` files optimized for Google Stitch screen generation. It translates the battle-tested anti-slop frontend engineering directives into Stitch's native semantic design language — descriptive, natural-language rules paired with precise values that Stitch's AI agent can interpret to produce premium, non-generic interfaces.\n\n  Line 11: The generated `DESIGN.md` serves as the **single source of truth** for prompting Stitch to generate new screens that align with a curated, high-agency design language. Stitch interprets design through **\"Visual Descriptions\"** supported by specific color values, typography specs, and component behaviors.\n\n  Line 14: - Access to Google Stitch via [labs.google/stitch](https://labs.google/stitch)\n\n  Line 18: Generate a `DESIGN.md` file that encodes:\n\n  Line 97: Encode these as explicit \"NEVER DO\" rules in the DESIGN.md:\n\n  Line 115: ## Output Format (DESIGN.md Structure)\n\n  Line 172: 1. Start with the atmosphere — understand the vibe before detailing tokens\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/12-principles-of-animation.md:\n  Line 6:   author: raphael-salaja\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/audit.md:\n  Line 42: - **Hard-coded colors**: Colors not using design tokens\n\n  Line 44: - **Inconsistent tokens**: Using wrong tokens, mixing token types\n\n  Line 47: **Score 0-4**: 0=No theming (hard-coded everything), 1=Minimal tokens (mostly hard-coded), 2=Partial (tokens exist but inconsistently used), 3=Good (tokens used, minor hard-coded values), 4=Excellent (full token system, dark mode works perfectly)\n\n  Line 110: - \"Hard-coded colors appear in 15+ components, should use design tokens\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/baseline.md:\n  Line 85: - SHOULD use existing theme or Tailwind CSS color tokens before introducing new ones\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/canvas-design.md:\n  Line 106: To create museum or magazine quality work, use the design philosophy as the foundation. Create one single page, highly visual, design-forward PDF or PNG output (unless asked for more pages). Generally use repeating patterns and perfect shapes. Treat the abstract philosophical design as if it were a scientific bible, borrowing the visual language of systematic observation—dense accumulation of marks, repeated elements, or layered patterns that build meaning through patient repetition and reward sustained viewing. Add sparse, clinical typography and systematic reference markers that suggest this could be a diagram from an imaginary discipline, treating the invisible subject with the same reverence typically reserved for documenting observable phenomena. Anchor the piece with simple phrase(s) or details positioned subtly, using a limited color palette that feels intentional and cohesive. Embrace the paradox of using analytical visual language to express ideas about human experience: the result should feel like an artifact that proves something ephemeral can be studied, mapped, and understood through careful attention. This is true art. \n\n  Line 108: **Text as a contextual element**: Text is always minimal and visual-first, but let context guide whether that means whisper-quiet labels or bold typographic gestures. A punk venue poster might have larger, more aggressive type than a minimalist ceramics studio identity. Most of the time, font should be thin. All use of fonts must be design-forward and prioritize visual communication. Regardless of text scale, nothing falls off the page and nothing overlaps. Every element must be contained within the canvas boundaries with proper margins. Check carefully that all text, graphics, and visual elements have breathing room and clear separation. This is non-negotiable for professional execution. **IMPORTANT: Use different fonts if writing text. Search the `./canvas-fonts` directory. Regardless of approach, sophistication is non-negotiable.**\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/distill.md:\n  Line 23:    - **Feature creep**: Too many options, actions, or paths forward\n\n  Line 73: - **Reduce choices**: Fewer buttons, fewer options, clearer path forward (paradox of choice is real)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/mastering-animate-presence.md:\n  Line 6:   author: raphael-salaja\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/colorize.md:\n  Line 256: Use two layers: primitive tokens (`--blue-500`) and semantic tokens (`--color-primary: var(--blue-500)`). For dark mode, only redefine the semantic layer; primitives stay the same.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/emil-design-eng.md:\n  Line 525:   fill: 'forwards',\n\n  Line 616:   animation: fadeIn 300ms ease-out forwards;\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/designer-skills-main/README.md:\n  Line 70: | design-systems | 11 | 3 | Build and maintain design systems: tokens, components, accessibility, theming, motion, governance, and localization. |\n\n  Line 89: | `/design-systems:tokenize` | design-systems | Extract and organize design tokens. |\n\n  Line 115: **Skills** are domain knowledge units — nouns. They teach Claude about a design topic: how to create a user persona, how to define design tokens, how to write a non-leading interview question.\n\n  Line 173: | Design tokens | design-systems | `/design-systems:tokenize` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/critique.md:\n  Line 248: - If findings are straightforward (e.g., only 1-2 clear issues), skip questions and go directly to Recommended Actions.\n\n  Line 251: Codex final-question gate: The user-visible response must either include the targeted questions or explicitly say `Questions skipped: <reason>` because the findings were straightforward. Each question must include 2-3 concrete answer options tied to the actual critique findings. Do not end with only open-ended questions.\n\n  Line 477: | 0 | Inconsistent everywhere; feels like different products stitched together |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.open