{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782489125819,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_QH376IJLMkcRJMJgT2AVC53k","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"Brand|Product|register|bolder|quieter|distill|realistic|AI|mock|layout|pre-flight|preflight|two-line|gapless|AIDA|dark|polish|redesign","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Anti-slop frontend skill for landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. The agent reads the brief, infers the right design direction, and ships interfaces that do not look templated. Real design systems when applicable, audit-first on redesigns, strict pre-flight check.\n\n  Line 8: > Landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. Not dashboards, not data tables, not multi-step product UI.\n\n  Line 18: 1. **Page kind** - landing (SaaS / consumer / agency / event), portfolio (dev / designer / creative studio), redesign (preserve vs overhaul), editorial / blog.\n\n  Line 19: 2. **Vibe words** the user used - \"minimalist\", \"calm\", \"Linear-style\", \"Awwwards\", \"brutalist\", \"premium consumer\", \"Apple-y\", \"playful\", \"serious B2B\", \"editorial\", \"agency-y\", \"glassy\", \"dark tech\".\n\n  Line 22: 5. **Brand assets that already exist** - logo, color, type, photography. For redesigns, these are starting material, not optional input (see Section 11).\n\n  Line 31: - *\"Reading this as: redesign of a public-sector service site, with a trust-first language, leaning toward GOV.UK Frontend or USWDS.\"*\n\n  Line 39: Do not default to: AI-purple gradients, centered hero over dark mesh, three equal feature cards, generic glassmorphism on everything, infinite-loop micro-animations everywhere, Inter + slate-900. These are the LLM defaults. Reach past them deliberately based on the design read.\n\n  Line 45: After the design read, set three dials. Every layout, motion, and density decision below is gated by these.\n\n  Line 61: | \"redesign - preserve\" | match existing | +1 | match existing |\n\n  Line 62: | \"redesign - overhaul\" | +2 | +2 | match existing |\n\n  Line 94: | GitHub-style devtool / community page | `@primer/css` or `@primer/react-brand` | Official Primer; Brand variant for marketing |\n\n  Line 98: | Modern accessible React foundation | `@radix-ui/themes` | Primitives + polished theme |\n\n  Line 100: | Tailwind-based modern SaaS / AI marketing | Tailwind v4 utilities + `dark:` variant | Default for indie + small team builds |\n\n  Line 129:   * **INTERACTIVITY ISOLATION:** Any component using Motion, scroll listeners, or pointer physics MUST be an isolated leaf with `'use client'` at the top. Server Components render static layouts only.\n\n  Line 152: * Contain page layouts using `max-w-[1400px] mx-auto` or `max-w-7xl`.\n\n  Line 153: * **Viewport Stability:** NEVER use `h-screen` for full-height Hero sections. ALWAYS use `min-h-[100dvh]` to prevent layout jumping on mobile (iOS Safari address bar).\n\n  Line 174:   * Serif is **very discouraged as the default font for any project.** \"It feels creative / premium / editorial\" is NOT a reason to reach for serif. The agent's default mental model that \"creative brief = serif\" is the single most-tested AI tell in production rounds.\n\n  Line 187: * **THE LILA RULE:** The \"AI Purple / Blue glow\" aesthetic is discouraged as a default. No automatic purple button glows, no random neon gradients. Use neutral bases (Zinc / Slate / Stone) with high-contrast singular accents (Emerald, Electric Blue, Deep Rose, Burnt Orange, etc.).\n\n  Line 188: * **Override:** if the brand or brief explicitly asks for purple / violet / lila, embrace it. But execute with intent: consistent palette, harmonised neutrals, restrained gradients. Not generic AI gradient slop.\n\n  Line 192: * **PREMIUM-CONSUMER PALETTE BAN (mandatory, second-most-recurring AI-tell):**\n\n  Line 193:   * For premium-consumer briefs (cookware, wellness, artisan, luxury, heritage craft, DTC home goods, etc.) the LLM default is **warm beige/cream + brass/clay/oxblood/ochre + espresso/ink dark text**. Concretely banned hex families as default backgrounds and accents:\n\n  Line 216: * For `VISUAL_DENSITY > 7`: generic card containers are banned. Data metrics breathe in plain layout.\n\n  Line 217: * **SHAPE CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Pick ONE corner-radius scale for the page and stick to it. Options: all-sharp (radius 0), all-soft (radius 12-16px), all-pill (full radius for interactive). Mixed systems are allowed only when there is a documented rule (e.g. \"buttons are full-pill, cards are 16px, inputs are 8px\") and that rule is followed everywhere. Round buttons in a square layout, or square cards on a pill-button page, is broken design.\n\n  Line 221: * **Loading:** Skeletal loaders matching the final layout's shape. Avoid generic circular spinners.\n\n  Line 238: * **HERO TOP PADDING CAP (mandatory):** Hero top padding max `pt-24` (≈6rem) at desktop. More than that means the hero content floats halfway down the viewport and reads as a layout bug, not as intentional space. If your hero needs more breathing room, increase font scale or asset size, not top padding.\n\n  Line 247: * **Navigation MUST render on a single line on desktop.** If items don't fit at `lg` (1024px), condense labels, drop secondary items, or move to a hamburger. A two-line nav at desktop is broken design.\n\n  Line 251: * **Section-Layout-Repetition Ban.** Once you use a layout family for a section (e.g., 3-column-image-cards, full-width-quote, split-text-image), that family can appear at most ONCE on the page. \"Selected commissions\" must not look like \"What we do.\" A landing page with 8 sections must use at least 4 different layout families.\n\n  Line 252: * **ZIGZAG ALTERNATION CAP (mandatory).** Alternating \"left-image + right-text\" then \"left-text + right-image\" zigzag layout = banal. Max 2 sections in a row with this image+text-split pattern. The 3rd consecutive image+text split is a Pre-Flight Fail. Break the pattern with a full-width section, a vertical-stack section, a bento grid, a marquee, or a different layout family.\n\n  Line 253: * **EYEBROW RESTRAINT (mandatory, the #1 violated rule in production tests).** An \"eyebrow\" is the small uppercase wide-tracking label sitting above a section headline (e.g. `FOUR COLORWAYS`, `SELECTED WORK`, `THE HARDWARE`, `Git-native task management`). Typical CSS signature: `text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em]`, `font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em]`. Every AI-built site puts an eyebrow above EVERY section header, producing the same templated rhythm. Hard rule:\n\n  Line 259: * **Bento Background Diversity (mandatory).** Bento and feature-grid sections cannot be 6 white-on-white cards with text inside. At least 2-3 cells in any multi-cell grid need real visual variation: a real image, a brand-appropriate gradient (not AI-purple), a pattern, a tinted background. A cream-on-cream bento with only typography inside reads as boring AI default, even when the rest of the page is good.\n\n  Line 260: * **Mobile collapse must be explicit per section.** For every multi-column layout, declare the `< 768px` fallback in the same component. No \"it'll work, Tailwind handles it\" assumptions.\n\n  Line 267: 1. **Image-generation tool first.** If ANY image-gen tool is available in the environment (`generate_image`, MCP image tool, IDE-integrated gen, OpenAI image tools, etc.) you MUST use it to create section-specific assets: hero photography, product shots, texture backgrounds, mood images. Generate at the right aspect ratio for the section. Do not skip this step because hand-rolled CSS feels faster.\n\n  Line 280: * **Always** ensure logos render in both light and dark mode (white-on-dark, black-on-light, or single-color theme variable).\n\n  Line 303: * **No data-dump sections.** A 20-row publication table, a 30-row award list, a giant pricing matrix on a marketing page = wrong layout. Use:\n\n  Line 314:   A spec sheet with 10 rows + a hairline under every row is the WORST default. Either group rows into 2-3 chunks with sparse dividers, or move to a card-per-spec layout.\n\n  Line 315: * **Spec sheets specifically (the Marrow-cookware pattern).** A long product specification table with `border-b` on every row is the AI default for cookware / hardware / apparel / artisan-goods briefs. Banned. Concrete alternatives:\n\n  Line 324:   - **Sounds like AI hallucination** (cute-but-wrong wordplay, forced metaphors that don't track, \"elegant nothing\" phrases)\n\n  Line 325:   - **Reads like an LLM trying to sound thoughtful** (passive-aggressive humility, fake-craftsman labels, mock-poetic micro-meta)\n\n  Line 326:   Rewrite every flagged string. If unsure whether a string makes sense, replace it with a plain functional sentence. AI-generated cute copy is worse than boring copy.\n\n  Line 329:   - Are explicitly labeled as mock (`<!-- mock -->`, \"example\", \"sample data\") - fine\n\n  Line 330:   - Are AI-invented spec aesthetics - banned. Don't fake engineering precision the brand doesn't claim.\n\n  Line 331: * **One copy register per page.** Don't mix technical mono (\"47 tasks · 0.6 ctx-switches/day\"), editorial prose, and marketing punch in the same composition unless the brand voice explicitly calls for it.\n\n  Line 345: * If the page is dark mode, ALL sections are dark mode. No light-mode-warm-paper section sandwiched between dark sections (or vice versa). The user must not feel they walked into a different website mid-scroll.\n\n  Line 347: * Default behaviour: pick light, dark, or auto (`prefers-color-scheme`) at the page level and lock it. Section-level background tints within the same theme family are fine (`bg-zinc-950` next to `bg-zinc-900`); flipping to `bg-amber-50` in the middle of a `bg-zinc-950` page is broken.\n\n  Line 348: * When using a design system with built-in theming (Radix Themes, shadcn/ui with `<Theme>`), set the theme ONCE in `layout.tsx` or the page root. Do not let individual sections override.\n\n  Line 358: * **Perpetual Micro-Interactions** (Pulse, Typewriter, Float, Shimmer, Carousel): Use when `MOTION_INTENSITY > 5` AND the section actively benefits from motion (status indicators, live feeds, AI-feel). **Not every card needs an infinite loop.** If a section is informational, leave it still. Apply Spring Physics (`type: \"spring\", stiffness: 100, damping: 20`) - no linear easing.\n\n  Line 361: * **MARQUEE MAX-ONE-PER-PAGE (mandatory).** Horizontal scrolling text marquees (\"logos endlessly scrolling\", \"manifesto scrolling sideways\", \"kinetic word strip\") are appropriate at most ONCE per page. Two or more marquees on the same page reads as lazy filler. Pick the one section where the marquee actually serves the content; the others get a different layout.\n\n  Line 374: gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);\n\n  Line 436: gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);\n\n  Line 514: * **Layout Transitions:** Use Motion's `layout` and `layoutId` props for visible state changes (re-ordering lists, expanding modals, shared elements between routes). Do not wrap static content in `layout` props \"for safety\" - it costs measurement work.\n\n  Line 519: ## 6. PERFORMANCE & ACCESSIBILITY GUARDRAILS\n\n  Line 532: * Design for **both modes from the start**. Never ship light-only or dark-only without explicit user instruction.\n\n  Line 533: * Use Tailwind `dark:` variant OR CSS variables for tokens. Pick one strategy per project.\n\n  Line 534: * **Do not prescribe specific dark-mode colors here.** The brief decides. Maintain visual hierarchy, brand identity, and WCAG AA contrast (AAA for body) across both modes.\n\n  Line 535: * Respect `prefers-color-scheme: dark`. Default to system preference unless the brand insists on one mode.\n\n  Line 557: * **8-10 (Asymmetric):** Masonry layouts, CSS Grid with fractional units (`grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr 1fr`), massive empty zones (`padding-left: 20vw`).\n\n  Line 558: * **MOBILE OVERRIDE:** For levels 4-10, asymmetric layouts above `md:` MUST collapse to strict single-column (`w-full`, `px-4`, `py-8`) on viewports `< 768px`.\n\n  Line 577: * **Tailwind `dark:` variant** (default for utility-first projects): every color utility paired with its dark variant (`bg-white dark:bg-zinc-950`, `text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100`).\n\n  Line 578: * **CSS variables** (for shadcn/ui, Radix Themes, or component libraries with theming): define semantic tokens (`--surface`, `--surface-elevated`, `--text-primary`, `--accent`) and swap values under `[data-theme=\"dark\"]` or `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)`.\n\n  Line 583: * **Hierarchy parity** - visual hierarchy that works in light must work in dark. If a CTA pops in light, it pops in dark.\n\n  Line 584: * **Brand fidelity** - primary brand color stays recognisable. Don't desaturate the brand into a dark mode.\n\n  Line 595: ## 9. AI TELLS (Forbidden Patterns)\n\n  Line 616: * **NO generic names.** \"John Doe\", \"Sarah Chan\", \"Jack Su\" → use creative, realistic, locale-appropriate names.\n\n  Line 628: * **Production-Ready Cleanliness:** Code visually clean, memorable, meticulously refined.\n\n  Line 630: ### 9.F Production-Test Tells (banned outright)\n\n  Line 636: * **NO \"Brand · No. 01\"-style sub-eyebrows.** \"Marrow · No. 01 · The 6-quart\" type micro-meta lines. Skip them.\n\n  Line 656: * **NO fake version footers** (\"v0.6.2-rc.1\", \"last sync 4s ago · main\") inside fake screenshots. Adds nothing, screams AI.\n\n  Line 661: * **NO \"We respect the French ones\"-style** mock-humble industry-references in body copy. Cute and AI-y.\n\n  Line 667: * **NO pills/labels/tags overlaid on images.** No `<span>` overlays on photos with tags like `Brand · 02`, `PLATE · BRAND`, `Field notes - journal`. Either let the image speak alone, or add a caption directly below (outside the image).\n\n  Line 677: * **NO `border-t` + `border-b` on every row of a long list / spec table.** Pick one (bottom-border between rows OR top-border above the group) and use it sparsely. A 10-row spec table with hairlines under each row is the laziest layout - see Section 4.9 for alternative UI components.\n\n  Line 785: This skill handles **greenfield builds AND redesigns**. Misclassifying the mode is the single biggest source of bad redesign output.\n\n  Line 792: If ambiguous, ask **once**: *\"Should this redesign preserve the existing brand, or are we starting visually from scratch?\"*\n\n  Line 796: * **Brand tokens** - primary / accent colors, type stack, logo treatment, radii.\n\n  Line 800: * **Patterns to retire** - AI-slop tells, broken layouts, dead links, generic stock imagery, perf traps.\n\n  Line 802: * **SEO baseline** - current ranking pages, meta titles, structured data, OG cards. **SEO migration is the #1 redesign risk.**\n\n  Line 822: * Visual debt is structural (broken IA, no design system, broken mobile) → **full redesign** with strict content preservation.\n\n  Line 823: * Brand itself is changing → **greenfield**.\n\n  Line 830: * Brand logo or wordmark.\n\n  Line 879: 1. **Visual sketch** - short ASCII or description of the layout.\n\n  Line 921: - [ ] **Page Theme Lock**: ONE theme (light, dark, or auto) for the whole page. No section flips to inverted mode mid-page (Section 4.11)?\n\n  Line 928: - [ ] **Premium-consumer palette check**: if the brief is premium-consumer (cookware / wellness / artisan / luxury), the palette is NOT the AI-default beige+brass+oxblood+espresso family? Different family from your previous premium-consumer project?\n\n  Line 935: - [ ] **Zigzag Alternation Cap**: no 3+ consecutive sections with the same image+text-split layout?\n\n  Line 940: - [ ] **Copy Self-Audit**: every visible string re-read, no grammatically-broken or AI-hallucinated phrases (\"free on its past\" type) shipped?\n\n  Line 944: - [ ] **Section-Layout-Repetition** check: no two sections share the same layout family (at least 4 different families across 8 sections)?\n\n  Line 948: - [ ] **No pills/labels overlaid on images** (no `Plate · Brand`, no `Field notes - journal`)?\n\n  Line 968: - [ ] **Mobile collapse** explicit (`w-full`, `px-4`, `max-w-7xl mx-auto`) for high-variance layouts?\n\n  Line 975: - [ ] **No AI Tells** from Section 9 (Inter as default, AI-purple, three-equal cards, Jane Doe, Acme, \"Quietly in use at\")?\n\n  Line 1012: # Primer Brand (GitHub marketing UI)\n\n  Line 1070: - https://design-system.service.gov.uk/styles/layout/\n\n  Line 1080: - https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/layout/grid/\n\n  Line 1084: - https://tailwindcss.com/docs/dark-mode\n\n  Line 1101: - https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Guides/Grid_layout\n\n  Line 1181: @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 3: description: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces with high design quality. Use this skill when the user asks to build web components, pages, or applications. Generates creative, polished code that avoids generic AI aesthetics.\n\n  Line 10: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces that avoid generic \"AI slop\" aesthetics. Implement real working code with exceptional attention to aesthetic details and creative choices. Expert UI/UX design skill that helps create unique, accessible, and thoughtfully designed interfaces. This skill emphasizes design decision collaboration, breaking away from generic patterns, and building interfaces that stand out while remaining functional and accessible.\n\n  Line 34: - **Editorial/magazine** - strong typography hierarchy, asymmetric layouts\n\n  Line 49: **NEVER Use These AI-Generated Aesthetics:**\n\n  Line 50: - **Fonts**: Inter, Roboto, Arial, system fonts as primary choice, Space Grotesk (overused by AI)\n\n  Line 52: - **Patterns**: Cookie-cutter layouts, predictable component arrangements\n\n  Line 152: 7. **Approval**: Have I asked before implementing colors, fonts, sizes, layouts?\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"Brand|Product|register|bolder|quieter|distill|realistic|AI|mock|layout|pre-flight|preflight|two-line|gapless|AIDA|dark|polish|redesign","time":{"start":1782489125800,"end":1782489125818}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07938b3e991fec89016a3ea025a0ac8190ae4476a5ed8ece42"}},"id":"prt_f04a1936900144bXs2gZ0MDMC2","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f04a141e6001ZNyHc5sl0xmpOy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782489125831,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_rvxH0IGqh8CGZjk50Yv4j8EP","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"OKLCH|color|palette|data|visualization|greenfield|brand|dark|layout|container|responsive","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 8: > Landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. Not dashboards, not data tables, not multi-step product UI.\n\n  Line 19: 2. **Vibe words** the user used - \"minimalist\", \"calm\", \"Linear-style\", \"Awwwards\", \"brutalist\", \"premium consumer\", \"Apple-y\", \"playful\", \"serious B2B\", \"editorial\", \"agency-y\", \"glassy\", \"dark tech\".\n\n  Line 20: 3. **Reference signals** - URLs they linked, screenshots they pasted, products they named, brands they're competing with.\n\n  Line 22: 5. **Brand assets that already exist** - logo, color, type, photography. For redesigns, these are starting material, not optional input (see Section 11).\n\n  Line 39: Do not default to: AI-purple gradients, centered hero over dark mesh, three equal feature cards, generic glassmorphism on everything, infinite-loop micro-animations everywhere, Inter + slate-900. These are the LLM defaults. Reach past them deliberately based on the design read.\n\n  Line 45: After the design read, set three dials. Every layout, motion, and density decision below is gated by these.\n\n  Line 57: | \"premium consumer / Apple-y / luxury / brand\" | 7-8 | 5-7 | 3-4 |\n\n  Line 91: | IBM-style B2B / enterprise analytics | `@carbon/react` + `@carbon/styles` | Official Carbon, mature data-density patterns |\n\n  Line 94: | GitHub-style devtool / community page | `@primer/css` or `@primer/react-brand` | Official Primer; Brand variant for marketing |\n\n  Line 100: | Tailwind-based modern SaaS / AI marketing | Tailwind v4 utilities + `dark:` variant | Default for indie + small team builds |\n\n  Line 129:   * **INTERACTIVITY ISOLATION:** Any component using Motion, scroll listeners, or pointer physics MUST be an isolated leaf with `'use client'` at the top. Server Components render static layouts only.\n\n  Line 152: * Contain page layouts using `max-w-[1400px] mx-auto` or `max-w-7xl`.\n\n  Line 153: * **Viewport Stability:** NEVER use `h-screen` for full-height Hero sections. ALWAYS use `min-h-[100dvh]` to prevent layout jumping on mobile (iOS Safari address bar).\n\n  Line 169:   * **Discouraged as default:** `Inter`. Pick `Geist`, `Outfit`, `Cabinet Grotesk`, `Satoshi`, or a brand-appropriate serif first.\n\n  Line 176:     - The brand brief literally names a serif font, OR\n\n  Line 177:     - The aesthetic family is genuinely editorial / luxury / publication / manuscript / heritage / vintage AND you can articulate why this specific serif fits this specific brand\n\n  Line 178:   * For everything else (creative agency, design studio, modern brand, premium consumer, portfolio, lifestyle), **default sans-serif display** (Geist Display, ABC Diatype, Söhne Breit, Cabinet Grotesk Display, Migra Sans, GT Walsheim, Inter Display, PP Neue Montreal). Sans display fonts are not \"boring\" — they are the default for the same reason black is the default in fashion.\n\n  Line 186: * Max 1 accent color. Saturation < 80% by default.\n\n  Line 188: * **Override:** if the brand or brief explicitly asks for purple / violet / lila, embrace it. But execute with intent: consistent palette, harmonised neutrals, restrained gradients. Not generic AI gradient slop.\n\n  Line 189: * **One palette per project.** Do not fluctuate between warm and cool grays within the same project.\n\n  Line 190: * **COLOR CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Once an accent color is chosen for a page, it is used on the WHOLE page. A warm-grey site does not suddenly get a blue CTA in section 7. A rose-accented site does not get a teal status badge in the footer. Pick one accent, lock it, audit every component before shipping.\n\n  Line 193:   * For premium-consumer briefs (cookware, wellness, artisan, luxury, heritage craft, DTC home goods, etc.) the LLM default is **warm beige/cream + brass/clay/oxblood/ochre + espresso/ink dark text**. Concretely banned hex families as default backgrounds and accents:\n\n  Line 197:   * This palette is BANNED as the default reach for premium-consumer briefs. Every premium-consumer site you have ever shipped uses this exact palette. The brand becomes invisible.\n\n  Line 206:   * **Palette-rotation rule:** if the previous premium-consumer project you generated used the beige+brass family, this one MUST use a different family. Do not ship the same warm-craft palette twice in a row.\n\n  Line 207:   * **Override:** the beige+brass+espresso palette is acceptable ONLY when the brand brief explicitly names those colors, or when the brand identity is genuinely vintage / artisan / warm-craft AND you can articulate why this specific palette fits this specific brand. Default-reaching for it because \"this is a cookware brief\" is banned.\n\n  Line 216: * For `VISUAL_DENSITY > 7`: generic card containers are banned. Data metrics breathe in plain layout.\n\n  Line 217: * **SHAPE CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Pick ONE corner-radius scale for the page and stick to it. Options: all-sharp (radius 0), all-soft (radius 12-16px), all-pill (full radius for interactive). Mixed systems are allowed only when there is a documented rule (e.g. \"buttons are full-pill, cards are 16px, inputs are 8px\") and that rule is followed everywhere. Round buttons in a square layout, or square cards on a pill-button page, is broken design.\n\n  Line 221: * **Loading:** Skeletal loaders matching the final layout's shape. Avoid generic circular spinners.\n\n  Line 238: * **HERO TOP PADDING CAP (mandatory):** Hero top padding max `pt-24` (≈6rem) at desktop. More than that means the hero content floats halfway down the viewport and reads as a layout bug, not as intentional space. If your hero needs more breathing room, increase font scale or asset size, not top padding.\n\n  Line 240:   1. Eyebrow (small uppercase label) OR brand strip OR neither - pick zero or one\n\n  Line 245:   - If you have an eyebrow AND a tagline below CTAs in the same hero, drop the tagline. If you have a brand strip AND a tagline, drop the tagline. One small text element per hero, max.\n\n  Line 251: * **Section-Layout-Repetition Ban.** Once you use a layout family for a section (e.g., 3-column-image-cards, full-width-quote, split-text-image), that family can appear at most ONCE on the page. \"Selected commissions\" must not look like \"What we do.\" A landing page with 8 sections must use at least 4 different layout families.\n\n  Line 252: * **ZIGZAG ALTERNATION CAP (mandatory).** Alternating \"left-image + right-text\" then \"left-text + right-image\" zigzag layout = banal. Max 2 sections in a row with this image+text-split pattern. The 3rd consecutive image+text split is a Pre-Flight Fail. Break the pattern with a full-width section, a vertical-stack section, a bento grid, a marquee, or a different layout family.\n\n  Line 259: * **Bento Background Diversity (mandatory).** Bento and feature-grid sections cannot be 6 white-on-white cards with text inside. At least 2-3 cells in any multi-cell grid need real visual variation: a real image, a brand-appropriate gradient (not AI-purple), a pattern, a tinted background. A cream-on-cream bento with only typography inside reads as boring AI default, even when the rest of the page is good.\n\n  Line 260: * **Mobile collapse must be explicit per section.** For every multi-column layout, declare the `< 768px` fallback in the same component. No \"it'll work, Tailwind handles it\" assumptions.\n\n  Line 270:    * Actual stock or brand URLs when the brief provides them\n\n  Line 277: * **Source: Simple Icons** (`https://cdn.simpleicons.org/{slug}/ffffff` for any color, or `simple-icons` npm package). Covers most known brands.\n\n  Line 279: * **Make-up the brand name? Then make-up an SVG mark too.** Generate a simple monogram (one letter in a circle, two-letter ligature, abstract glyph) rendered as an inline `<svg>` matching the page style. Plain text wordmarks for invented brand names look generic.\n\n  Line 280: * **Always** ensure logos render in both light and dark mode (white-on-dark, black-on-light, or single-color theme variable).\n\n  Line 281: * **LOGO-ONLY rule (mandatory):** logo wall = logos and nothing else. Do NOT print industry / category labels below each logo (no `Vercel` + `hosting` underneath, no `Stripe` + `payments`, no `Cloudflare` + `infra`). The logo is the credibility, the label adds nothing the user does not already know. Optional: brand name as alt-text for screen readers, optional link to the brand's site. That is it.\n\n  Line 303: * **No data-dump sections.** A 20-row publication table, a 30-row award list, a giant pricing matrix on a marketing page = wrong layout. Use:\n\n  Line 306:   - Different page entirely if the data is the product\n\n  Line 314:   A spec sheet with 10 rows + a hairline under every row is the WORST default. Either group rows into 2-3 chunks with sparse dividers, or move to a card-per-spec layout.\n\n  Line 328:   - Come from real data (brief, brand guidelines, public metrics) - fine\n\n  Line 329:   - Are explicitly labeled as mock (`<!-- mock -->`, \"example\", \"sample data\") - fine\n\n  Line 330:   - Are AI-invented spec aesthetics - banned. Don't fake engineering precision the brand doesn't claim.\n\n  Line 331: * **One copy register per page.** Don't mix technical mono (\"47 tasks · 0.6 ctx-switches/day\"), editorial prose, and marketing punch in the same composition unless the brand voice explicitly calls for it.\n\n  Line 345: * If the page is dark mode, ALL sections are dark mode. No light-mode-warm-paper section sandwiched between dark sections (or vice versa). The user must not feel they walked into a different website mid-scroll.\n\n  Line 347: * Default behaviour: pick light, dark, or auto (`prefers-color-scheme`) at the page level and lock it. Section-level background tints within the same theme family are fine (`bg-zinc-950` next to `bg-zinc-900`); flipping to `bg-amber-50` in the middle of a `bg-zinc-950` page is broken.\n\n  Line 348: * When using a design system with built-in theming (Radix Themes, shadcn/ui with `<Theme>`), set the theme ONCE in `layout.tsx` or the page root. Do not let individual sections override.\n\n  Line 356: * **Liquid Glass / Glassmorphism:** Appropriate for premium consumer, Apple-adjacent, luxury brand, or media-overlay vibes. Inappropriate for dashboards, public-sector, or \"boring B2B.\" When used, go beyond `backdrop-blur`: add a 1px inner border (`border-white/10`) and a subtle inner shadow (`shadow-[inset_0_1px_0_rgba(255,255,255,0.1)]`) for physical edge refraction. Provide a solid-fill fallback under `prefers-reduced-transparency`.\n\n  Line 361: * **MARQUEE MAX-ONE-PER-PAGE (mandatory).** Horizontal scrolling text marquees (\"logos endlessly scrolling\", \"manifesto scrolling sideways\", \"kinetic word strip\") are appropriate at most ONCE per page. Two or more marquees on the same page reads as lazy filler. Pick the one section where the marquee actually serves the content; the others get a different layout.\n\n  Line 514: * **Layout Transitions:** Use Motion's `layout` and `layoutId` props for visible state changes (re-ordering lists, expanding modals, shared elements between routes). Do not wrap static content in `layout` props \"for safety\" - it costs measurement work.\n\n  Line 532: * Design for **both modes from the start**. Never ship light-only or dark-only without explicit user instruction.\n\n  Line 533: * Use Tailwind `dark:` variant OR CSS variables for tokens. Pick one strategy per project.\n\n  Line 534: * **Do not prescribe specific dark-mode colors here.** The brief decides. Maintain visual hierarchy, brand identity, and WCAG AA contrast (AAA for body) across both modes.\n\n  Line 535: * Respect `prefers-color-scheme: dark`. Default to system preference unless the brand insists on one mode.\n\n  Line 544: * Apply grain / noise filters EXCLUSIVELY to fixed, `pointer-events-none` pseudo-elements (e.g., `fixed inset-0 z-[60] pointer-events-none`). NEVER on scrolling containers - continuous GPU repaints destroy mobile FPS.\n\n  Line 556: * **4-7 (Offset):** `margin-top: -2rem` overlaps, varied image aspect ratios (4:3 next to 16:9), left-aligned headers over center-aligned data.\n\n  Line 557: * **8-10 (Asymmetric):** Masonry layouts, CSS Grid with fractional units (`grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr 1fr`), massive empty zones (`padding-left: 20vw`).\n\n  Line 558: * **MOBILE OVERRIDE:** For levels 4-10, asymmetric layouts above `md:` MUST collapse to strict single-column (`w-full`, `px-4`, `py-8`) on viewports `< 768px`.\n\n  Line 568: * **8-10 (Cockpit):** Tight paddings. No card boxes; 1px lines separate data. Mandatory: `font-mono` for all numbers.\n\n  Line 577: * **Tailwind `dark:` variant** (default for utility-first projects): every color utility paired with its dark variant (`bg-white dark:bg-zinc-950`, `text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100`).\n\n  Line 578: * **CSS variables** (for shadcn/ui, Radix Themes, or component libraries with theming): define semantic tokens (`--surface`, `--surface-elevated`, `--text-primary`, `--accent`) and swap values under `[data-theme=\"dark\"]` or `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)`.\n\n  Line 581: The brief and brand decide. This skill enforces only:\n\n  Line 583: * **Hierarchy parity** - visual hierarchy that works in light must work in dark. If a CTA pops in light, it pops in dark.\n\n  Line 584: * **Brand fidelity** - primary brand color stays recognisable. Don't desaturate the brand into a dark mode.\n\n  Line 588: Respect `prefers-color-scheme` unless the brand insists. Add a manual toggle if either mode would lose key brand expression.\n\n  Line 608: * **NO oversized H1s** that just scream. Control hierarchy with weight + color, not raw scale.\n\n  Line 618: * **NO fake-perfect numbers.** Avoid `99.99%`, `50%`, `1234567`. Use organic, messy data (`47.2%`, `+1 (312) 847-1928`).\n\n  Line 619: * **NO startup-slop brand names.** \"Acme\", \"Nexus\", \"SmartFlow\", \"Cloudly\" → invent contextual, premium names that sound real.\n\n  Line 627: * **shadcn/ui customization:** Allowed, but NEVER in default state. Customize radii, colors, shadows, typography to the project aesthetic.\n\n  Line 645: * **The middle-dot (`·`) is rationed.** Maximum 1 per line in metadata strips. Do NOT use it as the default separator for everything (\"foo · bar · baz · qux · quux\"). If you need a separator family, prefer line breaks, hairlines, or columns.\n\n  Line 646: * **NO decorative colored status dots on every list/nav/badge.** A colored dot before \"ONE Q4 SLOT OPEN\" or before every nav link, or every task row - banned by default. Acceptable only when the dot conveys actual semantic state (a server status, an availability flag) and is used sparingly.\n\n  Line 670: * **NO \"Reservation 412 of 800\"-style live-stock counters** as decoration. Only if the brief is explicitly a limited-run waitlist with real data.\n\n  Line 677: * **NO `border-t` + `border-b` on every row of a long list / spec table.** Pick one (bottom-border between rows OR top-border above the group) and use it sparsely. A 10-row spec table with hairlines under each row is the laziest layout - see Section 4.9 for alternative UI components.\n\n  Line 681: * **Locale / city-name / time / weather strips are banned for 99% of briefs.** \"Lisbon, working with founders\" in the hero, \"1200-690 Lisbon, Portugal\" in the footer, \"Lisbon 14:23 · 18°C\" in the nav. These are agency-portfolio decoration tells. Allowed ONLY when: the brief explicitly describes a globally-distributed studio with timezone-relevant work, OR a travel-focused brand, OR a real-world physical venue. A single contact-address mention in the footer is fine; an atmospheric locale strip is not.\n\n  Line 785: This skill handles **greenfield builds AND redesigns**. Misclassifying the mode is the single biggest source of bad redesign output.\n\n  Line 789: * **Redesign - Preserve** - modernise without breaking the brand. Audit first, extract brand tokens, evolve gradually.\n\n  Line 790: * **Redesign - Overhaul** - new visual language on top of existing content. Treat as greenfield for visuals; preserve content and IA.\n\n  Line 792: If ambiguous, ask **once**: *\"Should this redesign preserve the existing brand, or are we starting visually from scratch?\"*\n\n  Line 796: * **Brand tokens** - primary / accent colors, type stack, logo treatment, radii.\n\n  Line 800: * **Patterns to retire** - AI-slop tells, broken layouts, dead links, generic stock imagery, perf traps.\n\n  Line 802: * **SEO baseline** - current ranking pages, meta titles, structured data, OG cards. **SEO migration is the #1 redesign risk.**\n\n  Line 806: * **Extract brand colors before applying Section 4.2.** A brand that is already purple stays purple - apply the LILA RULE's override.\n\n  Line 815: 3. **Color recalibration** - desaturate, unify neutrals, keep brand accent.\n\n  Line 823: * Brand itself is changing → **greenfield**.\n\n  Line 879: 1. **Visual sketch** - short ASCII or description of the layout.\n\n  Line 921: - [ ] **Page Theme Lock**: ONE theme (light, dark, or auto) for the whole page. No section flips to inverted mode mid-page (Section 4.11)?\n\n  Line 922: - [ ] **Color Consistency Lock**: one accent color used identically across all sections (Section 4.2)?\n\n  Line 927: - [ ] **Serif discipline**: if a serif is used, it is NOT Fraunces or Instrument_Serif (or it is, with explicit brand justification)? Different serif from your previous project?\n\n  Line 928: - [ ] **Premium-consumer palette check**: if the brief is premium-consumer (cookware / wellness / artisan / luxury), the palette is NOT the AI-default beige+brass+oxblood+espresso family? Different family from your previous premium-consumer project?\n\n  Line 932: - [ ] **Hero stack discipline**: max 4 text elements in hero (eyebrow OR brand strip, headline, subtext, CTAs)? No tiny tagline below CTAs, no trust micro-strip in hero?\n\n  Line 935: - [ ] **Zigzag Alternation Cap**: no 3+ consecutive sections with the same image+text-split layout?\n\n  Line 944: - [ ] **Section-Layout-Repetition** check: no two sections share the same layout family (at least 4 different families across 8 sections)?\n\n  Line 961: - [ ] **Content density** sane: no 20-row data tables, no fake-precise specs without justification, ≤ 25-word sub-paragraphs by default?\n\n  Line 968: - [ ] **Mobile collapse** explicit (`w-full`, `px-4`, `max-w-7xl mx-auto`) for high-variance layouts?\n\n  Line 985: The sections below are vendored reference content. They give the agent real install commands, real canonical doc links, and real working starter snippets for each design system named in Section 2. Use them to ground decisions in production reality, not training-data fiction.\n\n  Line 1013: npm install @primer/react-brand\n\n  Line 1066: - https://github.com/primer/brand\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"OKLCH|color|palette|data|visualization|greenfield|brand|dark|layout|container|responsive","time":{"start":1782489125807,"end":1782489125829}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07938b3e991fec89016a3ea025a0bc819095aa672adbf79af8"}},"id":"prt_f04a193aa0010r0SV7gRuukxUM","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f04a141e6001ZNyHc5sl0xmpOy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782489125834,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_wMxnek8OhoQWGBJMG9gCzwZ5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"motion|AnimatePresence|gesture|interaction|micro|reduced|performance|spring|transition|exit|FLIP|layout","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/slidev.md:\n  Line 63: | Animations | v-click, v-clicks, motion, transitions | [core-animations](references/core-animations.md) |\n\n  Line 68: | Layouts | Built-in slide layouts | [core-layouts](references/core-layouts.md) |\n\n  Line 103: | Canvas size | `canvasWidth`, `aspectRatio` | [layout-canvas-size](references/layout-canvas-size.md) |\n\n  Line 104: | Zoom slide | `zoom: 0.8` | [layout-zoom](references/layout-zoom.md) |\n\n  Line 105: | Scale elements | `<Transform :scale=\"0.5\">` | [layout-transform](references/layout-transform.md) |\n\n  Line 106: | Layout slots | `::right::`, `::default::` | [layout-slots](references/layout-slots.md) |\n\n  Line 108: | Global layers | `global-top.vue`, `global-bottom.vue` | [layout-global-layers](references/layout-global-layers.md) |\n\n  Line 109: | Draggable elements | `v-drag`, `<v-drag>` | [layout-draggable](references/layout-draggable.md) |\n\n  Line 178: | `image` / `image-left` / `image-right` | Image layouts |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/adapt.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Adapt designs across breakpoints, device contexts, and platform constraints with responsive interaction quality.\"\n\n  Line 53: - Swipe gestures where appropriate (lists, carousels)\n\n  Line 66: - Reduce navigation complexity\n\n  Line 73: - Two-column layouts (not single or three-column)\n\n  Line 80: - Touch targets 44x44px but allow denser layouts than phone\n\n  Line 87: - Multi-column layouts (use horizontal space)\n\n  Line 125: - Table-based layouts (for email client compatibility)\n\n  Line 130: - Deep links to web app for complex interactions\n\n  Line 146: - **CSS Grid/Flexbox**: Reflow layouts automatically\n\n  Line 156: - Remove hover-dependent interactions\n\n  Line 209: Start with base styles for mobile, use `min-width` queries to layer complexity. Desktop-first (`max-width`) means mobile loads unnecessary styles first.\n\n  Line 306: DevTools device emulation is useful for layout but misses:\n\n  Line 308: - Actual touch interactions\n\n  Line 314: **Test on at least**: One real iPhone, one real Android, a tablet if relevant. Cheap Android phones reveal performance issues you'll never see on simulators.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/harden.md:\n  Line 273: @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n\n  Line 277:     transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/canvas-design.md:\n  Line 17: To begin, create a VISUAL PHILOSOPHY (not layouts or templates) that will be interpreted through:\n\n  Line 57: Visual expression: Massive color blocks, sculptural typography (huge single words, tiny labels), Brutalist spatial divisions, Polish poster energy meets Le Corbusier. Ideas expressed through visual weight and spatial tension, not explanation. Text as rare, powerful gesture - never paragraphs, only essential words integrated into the visual architecture. Every element placed with the precision of a master craftsman.\n\n  Line 61: Visual expression: Geometric precision where color zones create meaning. Typography minimal - small sans-serif labels letting chromatic fields communicate. Think Josef Albers' interaction meets data visualization. Information encoded spatially and chromatically. Words only to anchor what color already shows. The result of painstaking chromatic calibration.\n\n  Line 108: **Text as a contextual element**: Text is always minimal and visual-first, but let context guide whether that means whisper-quiet labels or bold typographic gestures. A punk venue poster might have larger, more aggressive type than a minimalist ceramics studio identity. Most of the time, font should be thin. All use of fonts must be design-forward and prioritize visual communication. Regardless of text scale, nothing falls off the page and nothing overlaps. Every element must be contained within the canvas boundaries with proper margins. Check carefully that all text, graphics, and visual elements have breathing room and clear separation. This is non-negotiable for professional execution. **IMPORTANT: Use different fonts if writing text. Search the `./canvas-fonts` directory. Regardless of approach, sophistication is non-negotiable.**\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bolder.md:\n  Line 25:    - **Generic choices**: System fonts, basic colors, standard layouts\n\n  Line 28:    - **Static**: No motion, no energy, no life\n\n  Line 36:    - What are the constraints? (Brand guidelines, accessibility, performance)\n\n  Line 76: - **Asymmetric layouts**: Replace centered, balanced layouts with tension-filled asymmetry\n\n  Line 89: - **Micro-interactions**: Satisfying hover effects, click feedback, state changes.\n\n  Line 90: - **Transitions**: Smooth, noticeable transitions using ease-out-quart/quint/expo (not bounce or elastic, which cheapen the effect).\n\n  Line 104: - Overwhelm with motion (animation fatigue is real)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/distill.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Simplify noisy interfaces by removing non-essential complexity and restoring clear visual focus.\"\n\n  Line 8: Strip a design to its essence. Remove anything that doesn't earn its place: redundant elements, repeated information, decorative noise, cosmetic complexity.\n\n  Line 17: 1. **Identify complexity sources**:\n\n  Line 48: Systematically remove complexity across these dimensions:\n\n  Line 52: - **Progressive disclosure**: Hide complexity behind clear entry points (accordions, modals, step-through flows)\n\n  Line 62: - **Remove unnecessary cards**: Cards aren't needed for basic layout; use spacing and alignment instead\n\n  Line 68: - **Full-width**: Use available space generously instead of complex multi-column layouts\n\n  Line 99: - Oversimplify complex domains (match complexity to actual task complexity)\n\n  Line 109: - **Better performance**: Does simpler design load faster?\n\n  Line 111: ## Document Removed Complexity\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 29: - *\"Reading this as: B2B SaaS landing for technical buyers, with a Linear-style minimalist language, leaning toward Tailwind utilities + Geist + restrained motion.\"*\n\n  Line 39: Do not default to: AI-purple gradients, centered hero over dark mesh, three equal feature cards, generic glassmorphism on everything, infinite-loop micro-animations everywhere, Inter + slate-900. These are the LLM defaults. Reach past them deliberately based on the design read.\n\n  Line 45: After the design read, set three dials. Every layout, motion, and density decision below is gated by these.\n\n  Line 111: | Glassmorphism / \"frosted glass\" | `backdrop-filter`, layered borders, highlight overlays. Provide solid-fill fallback for `prefers-reduced-transparency`. |\n\n  Line 129:   * **INTERACTIVITY ISOLATION:** Any component using Motion, scroll listeners, or pointer physics MUST be an isolated leaf with `'use client'` at the top. Server Components render static layouts only.\n\n  Line 132: * **Animation:** **Motion** (the library formerly known as Framer Motion). Import from `motion/react` (`import { motion } from \"motion/react\"`). The `framer-motion` package still works as a legacy alias - prefer `motion/react` in new code.\n\n  Line 152: * Contain page layouts using `max-w-[1400px] mx-auto` or `max-w-7xl`.\n\n  Line 153: * **Viewport Stability:** NEVER use `h-screen` for full-height Hero sections. ALWAYS use `min-h-[100dvh]` to prevent layout jumping on mobile (iOS Safari address bar).\n\n  Line 216: * For `VISUAL_DENSITY > 7`: generic card containers are banned. Data metrics breathe in plain layout.\n\n  Line 217: * **SHAPE CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Pick ONE corner-radius scale for the page and stick to it. Options: all-sharp (radius 0), all-soft (radius 12-16px), all-pill (full radius for interactive). Mixed systems are allowed only when there is a documented rule (e.g. \"buttons are full-pill, cards are 16px, inputs are 8px\") and that rule is followed everywhere. Round buttons in a square layout, or square cards on a pill-button page, is broken design.\n\n  Line 221: * **Loading:** Skeletal loaders matching the final layout's shape. Avoid generic circular spinners.\n\n  Line 238: * **HERO TOP PADDING CAP (mandatory):** Hero top padding max `pt-24` (≈6rem) at desktop. More than that means the hero content floats halfway down the viewport and reads as a layout bug, not as intentional space. If your hero needs more breathing room, increase font scale or asset size, not top padding.\n\n  Line 244:   - **BANNED in the hero:** tiny tagline below CTAs (\"Works with GitHub, GitLab, and self-hosted Git\"), trust micro-strip (\"Used by engineering teams at...\"), pricing teaser (\"Free for solo, $10/user for teams\"), feature bullet list, social-proof avatar row. All of those move to dedicated sections directly below the hero.\n\n  Line 251: * **Section-Layout-Repetition Ban.** Once you use a layout family for a section (e.g., 3-column-image-cards, full-width-quote, split-text-image), that family can appear at most ONCE on the page. \"Selected commissions\" must not look like \"What we do.\" A landing page with 8 sections must use at least 4 different layout families.\n\n  Line 252: * **ZIGZAG ALTERNATION CAP (mandatory).** Alternating \"left-image + right-text\" then \"left-text + right-image\" zigzag layout = banal. Max 2 sections in a row with this image+text-split pattern. The 3rd consecutive image+text split is a Pre-Flight Fail. Break the pattern with a full-width section, a vertical-stack section, a bento grid, a marquee, or a different layout family.\n\n  Line 260: * **Mobile collapse must be explicit per section.** For every multi-column layout, declare the `< 768px` fallback in the same component. No \"it'll work, Tailwind handles it\" assumptions.\n\n  Line 303: * **No data-dump sections.** A 20-row publication table, a 30-row award list, a giant pricing matrix on a marketing page = wrong layout. Use:\n\n  Line 314:   A spec sheet with 10 rows + a hairline under every row is the WORST default. Either group rows into 2-3 chunks with sparse dividers, or move to a card-per-spec layout.\n\n  Line 325:   - **Reads like an LLM trying to sound thoughtful** (passive-aggressive humility, fake-craftsman labels, mock-poetic micro-meta)\n\n  Line 346: * The exception: if the brief explicitly calls for a \"Color Block Story\" or \"Theme Switch on Scroll\" device AND that is a deliberate composition (one full theme switch with a strong transition, not random alternation), it is allowed once per page.\n\n  Line 348: * When using a design system with built-in theming (Radix Themes, shadcn/ui with `<Theme>`), set the theme ONCE in `layout.tsx` or the page root. Do not let individual sections override.\n\n  Line 356: * **Liquid Glass / Glassmorphism:** Appropriate for premium consumer, Apple-adjacent, luxury brand, or media-overlay vibes. Inappropriate for dashboards, public-sector, or \"boring B2B.\" When used, go beyond `backdrop-blur`: add a 1px inner border (`border-white/10`) and a subtle inner shadow (`shadow-[inset_0_1px_0_rgba(255,255,255,0.1)]`) for physical edge refraction. Provide a solid-fill fallback under `prefers-reduced-transparency`.\n\n  Line 358: * **Perpetual Micro-Interactions** (Pulse, Typewriter, Float, Shimmer, Carousel): Use when `MOTION_INTENSITY > 5` AND the section actively benefits from motion (status indicators, live feeds, AI-feel). **Not every card needs an infinite loop.** If a section is informational, leave it still. Apply Spring Physics (`type: \"spring\", stiffness: 100, damping: 20`) - no linear easing.\n\n  Line 359: * **\"Motion claimed, motion shown.\"** If `MOTION_INTENSITY > 4`, the page must actually move: entry transitions on hero, scroll-reveal on key sections, hover physics on CTAs, at minimum. A static page that claims `MOTION_INTENSITY: 7` is broken. Conversely, if you cannot ship working motion in the available scope, drop the dial to 3 and ship a clean static page. Never half-build motion that breaks (cut-off ScrollTriggers, jumpy enters, missing cleanups).\n\n  Line 360: * **MOTION MUST BE MOTIVATED (mandatory).** Before adding any animation, ask: \"what does this animation communicate?\" Valid answers: hierarchy (drawing attention to the right thing), storytelling (revealing content in sequence that matches a narrative), feedback (acknowledging a user action), state transition (showing something changed). Invalid answer: \"it looked cool\". GSAP everywhere because GSAP is available is amateur. Each ScrollTrigger, each marquee, each pinned section needs a reason. If you cannot articulate the reason in one sentence, drop the animation.\n\n  Line 361: * **MARQUEE MAX-ONE-PER-PAGE (mandatory).** Horizontal scrolling text marquees (\"logos endlessly scrolling\", \"manifesto scrolling sideways\", \"kinetic word strip\") are appropriate at most ONCE per page. Two or more marquees on the same page reads as lazy filler. Pick the one section where the marquee actually serves the content; the others get a different layout.\n\n  Line 372: import { useReducedMotion } from \"motion/react\";\n\n  Line 434: import { useReducedMotion } from \"motion/react\";\n\n  Line 481: import { motion, useReducedMotion } from \"motion/react\";\n\n  Line 488:         <motion.li\n\n  Line 493:           transition={{\n\n  Line 500:         </motion.li>\n\n  Line 513: * **`requestAnimationFrame` loops that touch React state.** Use motion values (`useMotionValue` + `useTransform`) instead.\n\n  Line 514: * **Layout Transitions:** Use Motion's `layout` and `layoutId` props for visible state changes (re-ordering lists, expanding modals, shared elements between routes). Do not wrap static content in `layout` props \"for safety\" - it costs measurement work.\n\n  Line 526: * **Any motion above `MOTION_INTENSITY > 3` MUST honor `prefers-reduced-motion`.** This is non-negotiable.\n\n  Line 528: * In CSS: gate animations behind `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: no-preference)` or provide an override block under `@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)` that disables.\n\n  Line 529: * Infinite loops, parallax, scroll-hijack, and magnetic physics MUST collapse to static / instant under reduced motion.\n\n  Line 557: * **8-10 (Asymmetric):** Masonry layouts, CSS Grid with fractional units (`grid-template-columns: 2fr 1fr 1fr`), massive empty zones (`padding-left: 20vw`).\n\n  Line 558: * **MOBILE OVERRIDE:** For levels 4-10, asymmetric layouts above `md:` MUST collapse to strict single-column (`w-full`, `px-4`, `py-8`) on viewports `< 768px`.\n\n  Line 561: * **1-3 (Static):** No automatic animations. CSS `:hover` and `:active` states only. `prefers-reduced-motion` is the default mode anyway.\n\n  Line 562: * **4-7 (Fluid CSS):** `transition: all 0.3s cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1)`. `animation-delay` cascades for load-ins. Focus on `transform` and `opacity`.\n\n  Line 636: * **NO \"Brand · No. 01\"-style sub-eyebrows.** \"Marrow · No. 01 · The 6-quart\" type micro-meta lines. Skip them.\n\n  Line 638: **Section numbering & micro-labels**\n\n  Line 663: * **NO micro-meta-sentences under eyebrows.** Sentences like *\"Each of these is a feature we ship today, not a roadmap promise. The list will stay short on purpose.\"* sitting under a section heading are clutter. Eyebrow + Headline + Body is enough.\n\n  Line 677: * **NO `border-t` + `border-b` on every row of a long list / spec table.** Pick one (bottom-border between rows OR top-border above the group) and use it sparsely. A 10-row spec table with hairlines under each row is the laziest layout - see Section 4.9 for alternative UI components.\n\n  Line 723: * **Floating Speed Dial** - FAB springing into curved secondary actions.\n\n  Line 747: * **Liquid Swipe Transition** - Page transition like viscous liquid.\n\n  Line 776: * **Motion (`motion/react`)** - default for UI / Bento / state-change motion.\n\n  Line 799: * **Patterns to preserve** - signature interactions, recognisable hero, copy voice.\n\n  Line 800: * **Patterns to retire** - AI-slop tells, broken layouts, dead links, generic stock imagery, perf traps.\n\n  Line 816: 4. **Motion layer** - add `MOTION_INTENSITY`-appropriate micro-interactions to existing components.\n\n  Line 837: The Reference Vocabulary (Section 10) names patterns. The Block Library implements them with real props, real motion specs, and real code sketches.\n\n  Line 860:   transition/\n\n  Line 870:   motion: [3, 10]\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"motion|AnimatePresence|gesture|interaction|micro|reduced|performance|spring|transition|exit|FLIP|layout","time":{"start":1782489125812,"end":1782489125833}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07938b3e991fec89016a3ea025a0c881908dfbe0249c531fef"}},"id":"prt_f04a193b0001fP30J7Zram9P70","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f04a141e6001ZNyHc5sl0xmpOy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782489125914,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_hELZgaeL6s7eODJk29E7RnkR","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"accessibility|audit|critique|hardening|score|P0|P1|WCAG|performance|slop|production|contrast|ARIA|harden","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Anti-slop frontend skill for landing pages, portfolios, and redesigns. The agent reads the brief, infers the right design direction, and ships interfaces that do not look templated. Real design systems when applicable, audit-first on redesigns, strict pre-flight check.\n\n  Line 23: 6. **Quiet constraints** - accessibility-first audiences, public-sector, regulated industries, trust-first commerce, kids' products. These constraints OVERRIDE aesthetic preference.\n\n  Line 47: * **`DESIGN_VARIANCE: 8`** - 1 = Perfect Symmetry, 10 = Artsy Chaos\n\n  Line 54: | Signal | VARIANCE | MOTION | DENSITY |\n\n  Line 60: | \"trust-first / public-sector / regulated / accessibility-critical\" | 3-4 | 2-3 | 4-5 |\n\n  Line 65: | Use case | VARIANCE | MOTION | DENSITY |\n\n  Line 78: Use these (or user-overridden values) as global variables. Cross-references throughout this document refer to these exact variable names - never invent aliases like `LAYOUT_VARIANCE` or `ANIM_LEVEL`.\n\n  Line 89: | Microsoft / enterprise SaaS / dashboards | `@fluentui/react-components` or `@fluentui/web-components` | Official Fluent UI, Microsoft tokens, accessibility done |\n\n  Line 133: * **Fonts:** Always use `next/font` (Next.js) or self-host with `@font-face` + `font-display: swap`. Never link Google Fonts via `<link>` in production.\n\n  Line 170:   * **Override:** Inter is acceptable when the user explicitly asks for a neutral / standard / Linear-style feel, or when the brief is a public-sector / accessibility-first site.\n\n  Line 174:   * Serif is **very discouraged as the default font for any project.** \"It feels creative / premium / editorial\" is NOT a reason to reach for serif. The agent's default mental model that \"creative brief = serif\" is the single most-tested AI tell in production rounds.\n\n  Line 187: * **THE LILA RULE:** The \"AI Purple / Blue glow\" aesthetic is discouraged as a default. No automatic purple button glows, no random neon gradients. Use neutral bases (Zinc / Slate / Stone) with high-contrast singular accents (Emerald, Electric Blue, Deep Rose, Burnt Orange, etc.).\n\n  Line 188: * **Override:** if the brand or brief explicitly asks for purple / violet / lila, embrace it. But execute with intent: consistent palette, harmonised neutrals, restrained gradients. Not generic AI gradient slop.\n\n  Line 190: * **COLOR CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Once an accent color is chosen for a page, it is used on the WHOLE page. A warm-grey site does not suddenly get a blue CTA in section 7. A rose-accented site does not get a teal status badge in the footer. Pick one accent, lock it, audit every component before shipping.\n\n  Line 201:     - **Black and Tan:** true off-black + warm tan, sharp contrast, no beige\n\n  Line 210: * **ANTI-CENTER BIAS:** Centered Hero / H1 sections are avoided when `DESIGN_VARIANCE > 4`. Force \"Split Screen\" (50/50), \"Left-aligned content / right-aligned asset\", \"Asymmetric white-space\", or scroll-pinned structures.\n\n  Line 225: * **BUTTON CONTRAST CHECK (mandatory, a11y):** Before shipping any button, verify the button text is readable against the button background. White button + white text, `bg-white` CTA with `text-white` label, transparent button against the page background with no border → all banned. Audit every CTA: contrast ratio WCAG AA min (4.5:1 for body, 3:1 for large text 18px+). Same rule applies to ghost buttons over photographic backgrounds (use a backdrop, scrim, or stroke).\n\n  Line 228: * **FORM CONTRAST CHECK (mandatory, a11y):** Form inputs, placeholder text, focus rings, helper text, and error text all pass WCAG AA contrast against the section background. Light placeholders on a near-white form, white form on white page section, form labels grayer than 4.5:1 contrast → all banned. Audit every form before shipping.\n\n  Line 253: * **EYEBROW RESTRAINT (mandatory, the #1 violated rule in production tests).** An \"eyebrow\" is the small uppercase wide-tracking label sitting above a section headline (e.g. `FOUR COLORWAYS`, `SELECTED WORK`, `THE HARDWARE`, `Git-native task management`). Typical CSS signature: `text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em]`, `font-mono text-[10.5px] uppercase tracking-[0.22em]`. Every AI-built site puts an eyebrow above EVERY section header, producing the same templated rhythm. Hard rule:\n\n  Line 264: Landing pages and portfolios are **visual products**. Text-only pages with fake-screenshot divs are slop.\n\n  Line 534: * **Do not prescribe specific dark-mode colors here.** The brief decides. Maintain visual hierarchy, brand identity, and WCAG AA contrast (AAA for body) across both modes.\n\n  Line 554: ### DESIGN_VARIANCE (Level 1-10)\n\n  Line 582: * **Contrast** - WCAG AA minimum for body text, AAA target for hero copy.\n\n  Line 604: * **NO custom mouse cursors.** Outdated, accessibility-hostile, perf-hostile.\n\n  Line 619: * **NO startup-slop brand names.** \"Acme\", \"Nexus\", \"SmartFlow\", \"Cloudly\" → invent contextual, premium names that sound real.\n\n  Line 687: **Em-dash (`—`) is COMPLETELY banned.** It is the LLM's signature stylistic crutch and it is the #1 visual Tell in production tests. There is no \"limited use\" allowance, no \"natural language frequency\" allowance, no \"in body copy is fine\" allowance. None.\n\n  Line 800: * **Patterns to retire** - AI-slop tells, broken layouts, dead links, generic stock imagery, perf traps.\n\n  Line 801: * **Dial reading of the existing site** - infer current `DESIGN_VARIANCE` / `MOTION_INTENSITY` / `VISUAL_DENSITY`. That's your starting point, not the baseline.\n\n  Line 808: * **Honor existing accessibility wins.** Do not regress focus states, alt text, keyboard nav, contrast.\n\n  Line 886: 8. **References** - links to real examples in production.\n\n  Line 919: - [ ] **Redesign mode** detected and audit performed (if applicable, Section 11)?\n\n  Line 924: - [ ] **Button Contrast Check**: every CTA text is readable against its background (no white-on-white, WCAG AA 4.5:1)?\n\n  Line 926: - [ ] **Form Contrast Check**: form inputs, placeholders, focus rings, labels all pass WCAG AA against the section background?\n\n  Line 985: The sections below are vendored reference content. They give the agent real install commands, real canonical doc links, and real working starter snippets for each design system named in Section 2. Use them to ground decisions in production reality, not training-data fiction.\n\n  Line 1136: - strong contrast fallbacks\n\n  Line 1152:   backdrop-filter: blur(24px) saturate(180%) contrast(1.05);\n\n  Line 1153:   -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(24px) saturate(180%) contrast(1.05);\n\n  Line 1202: **Important:** `prefers-reduced-transparency` has uneven browser support; test it. Always provide enough contrast even without blur.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 3: description: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces with high design quality. Use this skill when the user asks to build web components, pages, or applications. Generates creative, polished code that avoids generic AI aesthetics.\n\n  Line 10: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces that avoid generic \"AI slop\" aesthetics. Implement real working code with exceptional attention to aesthetic details and creative choices. Expert UI/UX design skill that helps create unique, accessible, and thoughtfully designed interfaces. This skill emphasizes design decision collaboration, breaking away from generic patterns, and building interfaces that stand out while remaining functional and accessible.\n\n  Line 23: 3. **Constraints**: Technical requirements (framework, performance, accessibility)?\n\n  Line 35: - **Brutalist/raw** - exposed structure, harsh contrasts, intentionally rough\n\n  Line 43: - Then implement with precision: production-grade, visually striking, memorable\n\n  Line 74: - Typography combinations that create contrast\n\n  Line 96:    - Create hierarchy through typography scale, color contrast, and spatial relationships\n\n  Line 123: - Accents are saturated enough to create clear contrast\n\n  Line 149: 4. **Accessibility**: Does it meet WCAG AA standards? (contrast, touch targets, keyboard nav)\n\n  Line 177:    - Use saturated colors for clear contrast against neutrals\n\n  Line 203: Accent colors should have clear contrast with both:\n\n  Line 213: - Ensure sufficient contrast for color-blind users\n\n  Line 214: - Follow WCAG 2.1 AA: minimum 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text\n\n  Line 241: - **Body Text**: Prioritize legibility, reading comfort, accessibility\n\n  Line 247: - Prefer variable fonts for fine-tuned control and performance\n\n  Line 270: - **Ratio**: Major third (1.25x) for moderate contrast, Perfect fourth (1.333x) for dramatic\n\n  Line 302: When using multiple typefaces, create contrast through:\n\n  Line 303: - **Category contrast**: Serif + Sans-serif (classic, clear distinction)\n\n  Line 304: - **Weight contrast**: Light + Bold (dynamic, energetic)\n\n  Line 305: - **Personality contrast**: Geometric + Humanist (modern + warm)\n\n  Line 542: - Follow WCAG 2.1 AA guidelines\n\n  Line 551: - Add accessibility attributes:\n\n  Line 580:    - Verify accessibility\n\n  Line 593: - Check color contrast ratios\n\n  Line 698: - Validate accessibility (it enables creativity, not limits it)\n\n  Line 710: - WCAG 2.1 Guidelines: https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/quickref/\n\n  Line 716: - ACCESSIBILITY.md - Accessibility essentials (WCAG AA baseline)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/output-skill.md:\n  Line 10: Treat every task as production-critical. A partial output is a broken output. Do not optimize for brevity — optimize for completeness. If the user asks for a full file, deliver the full file. If the user asks for 5 components, deliver 5 components. No exceptions.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 14: Brand: asymmetric compositions, fluid spacing with `clamp()`, intentional grid-breaking for emphasis. Rhythm through contrast: tight groupings paired with generous separations.\n\n  Line 99: - Use the fewest dimensions needed for clear hierarchy. Space alone can be enough; generous whitespace around an element draws the eye. Some of the most polished designs achieve rhythm with just space and weight. Add color or size contrast only when simpler means aren't sufficient.\n\n  Line 106: | **Color** | High contrast | Similar tones |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/delight.md:\n  Line 253: **WARNING**: Avoid cliched loading messages like \"Herding pixels\", \"Teaching robots to dance\", \"Consulting the magic 8-ball\", \"Counting backwards from infinity\". These are AI-slop copy, instantly recognizable as machine-generated. Write messages that are specific to what your product actually does.\n\n  Line 293: - Ignore accessibility (animate responsibly, provide alternatives)\n\n  Line 295: - Sacrifice performance for delight\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/SKILL.md:\n  Line 155: - Always add `alt` text for accessibility\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/minimalist-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Clean editorial-style interfaces. Warm monochrome palette, typographic contrast, flat bento grids, muted pastels. No gradients, no heavy shadows.\n\n  Line 10: Description: An advanced frontend engineering directive for generating highly refined, ultra-minimalist, \"document-style\" web interfaces analogous to top-tier workspace platforms. This protocol strictly enforces a high-contrast warm monochrome palette, bespoke typographic hierarchies, meticulous structural macro-whitespace, bento-grid layouts, and an ultra-flat component architecture with deliberate muted pastel accents. It actively rejects standard generic SaaS design trends.\n\n  Line 25: The interface must rely on extreme typographic contrast and premium font selection to establish an editorial feel.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:\n  Line 2: name: fixing-motion-performance\n\n  Line 3: description: Audit and fix animation performance issues including layout thrashing, compositor properties, scroll-linked motion, and blur effects. Use when animations stutter, transitions jank, or reviewing CSS/JS animation performance.\n\n  Line 6: # fixing-motion-performance\n\n  Line 8: Fix animation performance issues.\n\n  Line 12: - `/fixing-motion-performance`\n\n  Line 15: - `/fixing-motion-performance <file>`\n\n  Line 99: - validate layer behavior with tooling when performance matters\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/brutalist-skill.md:\n  Line 3: description: Raw mechanical interfaces fusing Swiss typographic print with military terminal aesthetics. Rigid grids, extreme type scale contrast, utilitarian color, analog degradation effects. For data-heavy dashboards, portfolios, or editorial sites that need to feel like declassified blueprints.\n\n  Line 10: **Description:** Advanced proficiency in architecting web interfaces that synthesize mid-century Swiss Typographic design, industrial manufacturing manuals, and retro-futuristic aerospace/military terminal interfaces. This discipline requires absolute mastery over rigid modular grids, extreme typographic scale contrast, purely utilitarian color palettes, and the programmatic simulation of analog degradation (halftones, CRT scanlines, bitmap dithering). The objective is to construct digital environments that project raw functionality, mechanical precision, and high data density, deliberately discarding conventional consumer UI patterns.\n\n  Line 17: *   **Characteristics:** High-contrast light modes (newsprint/off-white substrates). Reliance on monolithic, heavy sans-serif typography. Unforgiving structural grids outlined by visible dividing lines. Aggressive, asymmetric use of negative space punctuated by oversized, viewport-bleeding numerals or letterforms. Heavy use of primary red as an alert/accent color.\n\n  Line 90: 1.  **Grid Determinism:** Utilize `display: grid; gap: 1px;` with contrasting parent/child background colors to generate mathematically perfect, razor-thin dividing lines without complex border declarations.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/overdrive.md:\n  Line 24: 2. **{{ask_instruction}}** to present these directions and get the user's pick before writing any code. Explain trade-offs (browser support, performance cost, complexity).\n\n  Line 45: ### For performance-critical UI\n\n  Line 78: - **Web Animations API** (all browsers): JavaScript-driven animations with the performance of CSS. Composable, cancellable, reversible. The foundation for complex choreography.\n\n  Line 80: ### Push performance boundaries\n\n  Line 83: - **WASM**: near-native performance for computation-heavy features. Image processing, physics simulations, codecs.\n\n  Line 122: - Ignore `prefers-reduced-motion`. This is an accessibility requirement, not a suggestion\n\n  Line 134: - **The accessibility test**: Enable reduced motion. Still beautiful?\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/animate.md:\n  Line 8: > **Additional context needed**: performance constraints.\n\n  Line 35:    - What's the performance budget? (Mobile-first? Complex page?)\n\n  Line 193: - Ignore `prefers-reduced-motion` (this is an accessibility violation)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/optimize.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Diagnose and fix UI performance issues that affect rendering, animation, loading, and interaction responsiveness.\"\n\n  Line 12: Understand current performance and identify problems:\n\n  Line 15:    - **Core Web Vitals**: LCP, FID/INP, CLS scores\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"accessibility|audit|critique|hardening|score|P0|P1|WCAG|performance|slop|production|contrast|ARIA|harden","time":{"start":1782489125900,"end":1782489125914}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07938b3e991fec89016a3ea025a0d081908f7bb8c71f021710"}},"id":"prt_f04a193b5001IxIubMoeMa6iLf","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f04a141e6001ZNyHc5sl0xmpOy"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782489125916,"sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_issVp6y36IArTwhMkKebJDAV","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"DESIGN.md|Style Reference|extract|author|stitch|tokens|component|documentation|verbatim|PRODUCT.md|semantic","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/taste-skill.md:\n  Line 89: | Microsoft / enterprise SaaS / dashboards | `@fluentui/react-components` or `@fluentui/web-components` | Official Fluent UI, Microsoft tokens, accessibility done |\n\n  Line 90: | Google-ish UI, Material-flavored product | `@material/web` + Material 3 tokens | Official, theme-able via Material Theming |\n\n  Line 92: | Shopify app surfaces | `polaris.js` web components / Polaris React | Required for Shopify admin UI |\n\n  Line 93: | Atlassian / Jira-style product | `@atlaskit/*` + `@atlaskit/tokens` | Official Atlassian DS |\n\n  Line 99: | Modern SaaS where you own the components | shadcn/ui (`npx shadcn@latest add ...`) | You own the code, easy to customise; never ship default state |\n\n  Line 102: **Honesty rule:** if the brief reads as one of the systems above, install and use the **official** package. Do not recreate its CSS by hand. Do not import a system's tokens but then override 90% of them.\n\n  Line 104: **One system per project.** Do not mix Fluent React with Carbon in the same tree. Do not import shadcn/ui components into a Material 3 app.\n\n  Line 107: For these directions, there is **no single official package**. Build with native CSS + Tailwind + a maintained component library. Be honest in code comments about what is borrowed inspiration vs. official material.\n\n  Line 128:   * **RSC SAFETY:** Global state works ONLY in Client Components. In Next.js, wrap providers in a `\"use client\"` component.\n\n  Line 129:   * **INTERACTIVITY ISOLATION:** Any component using Motion, scroll listeners, or pointer physics MUST be an isolated leaf with `'use client'` at the top. Server Components render static layouts only.\n\n  Line 144: * **One family per project.** Do not mix Phosphor with Lucide in the same component tree.\n\n  Line 190: * **COLOR CONSISTENCY LOCK (mandatory):** Once an accent color is chosen for a page, it is used on the WHOLE page. A warm-grey site does not suddenly get a blue CTA in section 7. A rose-accented site does not get a teal status badge in the footer. Pick one accent, lock it, audit every component before shipping.\n\n  Line 256:   - **Pre-Flight Check is mechanical:** count instances of `uppercase tracking` (or similar small-caps mono labels above headlines) across all section components. If count > ceil(sectionCount / 3), the output fails.\n\n  Line 260: * **Mobile collapse must be explicit per section.** For every multi-column layout, declare the `< 768px` fallback in the same component. No \"it'll work, Tailwind handles it\" assumptions.\n\n  Line 293: * Use a real component preview (an actual mini-version of the UI inside the page)\n\n  Line 307: * **Long lists need a different UI component, not a longer list.** Default `<ul>` with bullets / `divide-y` rows is the lazy choice. If you have > 5 items, reach for one of these instead:\n\n  Line 533: * Use Tailwind `dark:` variant OR CSS variables for tokens. Pick one strategy per project.\n\n  Line 578: * **CSS variables** (for shadcn/ui, Radix Themes, or component libraries with theming): define semantic tokens (`--surface`, `--surface-elevated`, `--text-primary`, `--accent`) and swap values under `[data-theme=\"dark\"]` or `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)`.\n\n  Line 646: * **NO decorative colored status dots on every list/nav/badge.** A colored dot before \"ONE Q4 SLOT OPEN\" or before every nav link, or every task row - banned by default. Acceptable only when the dot conveys actual semantic state (a server status, an availability flag) and is used sparingly.\n\n  Line 655: * **NO div-based fake product UI in the hero** (fake task list, fake terminal, fake dashboard built from styled divs). It is the #1 LLM-design Tell. Use a real screenshot, a generated image, a real component preview, or none at all.\n\n  Line 677: * **NO `border-t` + `border-b` on every row of a long list / spec table.** Pick one (bottom-border between rows OR top-border above the group) and use it sparsely. A 10-row spec table with hairlines under each row is the laziest layout - see Section 4.9 for alternative UI components.\n\n  Line 683: * **ZERO decorative status dots by default.** A coloured dot before nav items, before list rows, before badges, before status labels is a Tell. Only acceptable when conveying real semantic state (a live indicator on actual server status, a live availability flag) and limited to one per page section.\n\n  Line 777: * **GSAP + ScrollTrigger** - for full-page scrolltelling and scroll hijacks. Isolate in dedicated leaf components with `useEffect` cleanup.\n\n  Line 779: * **NEVER mix GSAP / Three.js with Motion in the same component tree.** They fight over the same frames.\n\n  Line 789: * **Redesign - Preserve** - modernise without breaking the brand. Audit first, extract brand tokens, evolve gradually.\n\n  Line 796: * **Brand tokens** - primary / accent colors, type stack, logo treatment, radii.\n\n  Line 816: 4. **Motion layer** - add `MOTION_INTENSITY`-appropriate micro-interactions to existing components.\n\n  Line 880: 2. **Props API** - the component's interface.\n\n  Line 933: - [ ] **EYEBROW COUNT (mechanical)**: count instances of `uppercase tracking` micro-labels above section headlines across all components. Count ≤ ceil(sectionCount / 3)? Hero counts as 1.\n\n  Line 946: - [ ] **Long lists use the right UI component** (not default `<ul>` with `divide-y` for > 5 items - see Section 4.9 alternatives)?\n\n  Line 959: - [ ] **No decorative dots** (zero by default, only for real semantic state)?\n\n  Line 967: - [ ] **Dark mode** tokens defined and tested in both modes?\n\n  Line 974: - [ ] **Motion** isolated in client-leaf components with `'use client'` at the top, memoized?\n\n  Line 994: npm install @fluentui/react-components\n\n  Line 997: npm install @fluentui/web-components @fluentui/tokens\n\n  Line 1005: # shadcn/ui (open code, owned components)\n\n  Line 1022: yarn add @atlaskit/css-reset @atlaskit/tokens @atlaskit/button @atlaskit/badge @atlaskit/section-message @atlaskit/card\n\n  Line 1036: - https://github.com/material-components/material-web\n\n  Line 1042: - https://fluent2.microsoft.design/components/web/react/\n\n  Line 1044: - https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/fluent-ui/web-components/\n\n  Line 1050: - https://carbondesignsystem.com/developing/web-components-tutorial/overview/\n\n  Line 1053: - https://shopify.dev/docs/api/app-home/web-components\n\n  Line 1055: - https://polaris-react.shopify.com/components\n\n  Line 1059: - https://atlassian.design/components/button/examples\n\n  Line 1061: - https://atlassian.design/tokens/design-tokens\n\n  Line 1069: - https://design-system.service.gov.uk/components/button/\n\n  Line 1074: - https://designsystem.digital.gov/documentation/developers/\n\n  Line 1075: - https://designsystem.digital.gov/components/button/\n\n  Line 1076: - https://designsystem.digital.gov/components/card/\n\n  Line 1081: - https://getbootstrap.com/docs/5.3/components/card/\n\n  Line 1088: - https://www.radix-ui.com/themes/docs/components/theme\n\n  Line 1089: - https://www.radix-ui.com/themes/docs/components/card\n\n  Line 1094: - https://ui.shadcn.com/docs/components/card\n\n  Line 1107: - https://developer.apple.com/documentation/TechnologyOverviews/liquid-glass\n\n  Line 1108: - https://developer.apple.com/documentation/TechnologyOverviews/adopting-liquid-glass\n\n  Line 1109: - https://developer.apple.com/documentation/SwiftUI/Material\n\n  Line 1118: Apple documents Liquid Glass inside Apple's Human Interface Guidelines and Developer Documentation for **Apple platforms**. It is a dynamic material used across Apple platform UI. Apple's native implementation belongs to Apple platform APIs and system components, **not a public web CSS package**.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/bencium-innovative-ux-designer.md:\n  Line 3: description: Create distinctive, production-grade frontend interfaces with high design quality. Use this skill when the user asks to build web components, pages, or applications. Generates creative, polished code that avoids generic AI aesthetics.\n\n  Line 52: - **Patterns**: Cookie-cutter layouts, predictable component arrangements\n\n  Line 482: - Strongly prefer shadcn components (v4, pre-installed in `@/components/ui`)\n\n  Line 483: - Import individually: `import { Button } from \"@/components/ui/button\";`\n\n  Line 485: - Avoid creating custom components with names that clash with shadcn\n\n  Line 545: - Use semantic HTML for screen reader compatibility\n\n  Line 554:   - `role` attributes when semantic HTML isn't sufficient\n\n  Line 616: import { Button } from \"@/components/ui/button\";\n\n  Line 718: - RESPONSIVE-DESIGN.md - Mobile-first breakpoints and patterns\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/ui-skills-root.md:\n  Line 6:   author: ibelick\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/output-skill.md:\n  Line 10: Treat every task as production-critical. A partial output is a broken output. Do not optimize for brevity — optimize for completeness. If the user asks for a full file, deliver the full file. If the user asks for 5 components, deliver 5 components. No exceptions.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/layout.md:\n  Line 54: - **Spacing system**: Use a consistent scale (a framework's built-in scale like Tailwind's, rem-based tokens, or a custom system). The specific values matter less than consistency.\n\n  Line 63: - Use a consistent spacing scale (framework scales like Tailwind, rem-based tokens, or a custom scale all work). What matters is that values come from a defined set, not arbitrary numbers.\n\n  Line 65: - Name tokens semantically if using custom properties: `--space-xs` through `--space-xl`, not `--spacing-8`\n\n  Line 78: - **Use Flexbox for 1D layouts**: Rows of items, nav bars, button groups, card contents, most component internals.\n\n  Line 81: - Use **container queries** for components, viewport queries for page layouts. A card in a narrow sidebar can stay compact while the same card in a main content area expands automatically:\n\n  Line 152: Each variant MUST declare a `density` param. Drive all spacing tokens in the variant's scoped CSS through `calc(var(--p-density, 1) * <base>)`: paddings, gaps, column widths. Users slide from airy to packed and see layout re-breathe with no regeneration.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/SKILL.md:\n  Line 15:   author: Joe Hu\n\n  Line 35:    - **Read for theme**: Section 1 (light tokens) or Section 9 (dark tokens)\n\n  Line 79: See design-system.md **Section 9** for complete dark theme tokens, or **Section 1** for light theme tokens.\n\n  Line 202: - [`design-system.md`](design-system.md) — Complete design tokens (light + dark), card CSS/HTML, layout templates, and skeleton\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/design-system.md:\n  Line 3: Complete design tokens, card components, layout templates, and HTML skeleton for generating Apple-inspired bento grid presentations. Supports both light and dark themes.\n\n  Line 7: 1. [Design Tokens](#1-design-tokens) — Colors, typography, spacing (light theme)\n\n  Line 11: 5. [Card Components](#5-card-components) — Hero, Stat, Category, Bar Chart, Badge, Quote, Highlight\n\n  Line 12: 6. [Pill / Tag Component](#6-pill--tag-component) — Reusable tag styling\n\n  Line 15: 9. [Dark Theme](#9-dark-theme) — Complete dark theme tokens, card overrides, and skeleton\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/apple-bento-grid-main/README.md:\n  Line 163: ├── design-system.md      # Complete design tokens, CSS/HTML for all components\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/minimalist-skill.md:\n  Line 10: Description: An advanced frontend engineering directive for generating highly refined, ultra-minimalist, \"document-style\" web interfaces analogous to top-tier workspace platforms. This protocol strictly enforces a high-contrast warm monochrome palette, bespoke typographic hierarchies, meticulous structural macro-whitespace, bento-grid layouts, and an ultra-flat component architecture with deliberate muted pastel accents. It actively rejects standard generic SaaS design trends.\n\n  Line 32: Color is a scarce resource, utilized only for semantic meaning or subtle accents.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:\n  Line 30: - reviewing components that use will-change, transforms, or measurement\n\n  Line 120: - never partially migrate APIs or mix styles within the same component\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/brutalist-skill.md:\n  Line 55: *   **Background:** `#F4F4F0` or `#EAE8E3` (Matte, unbleached documentation paper).\n\n  Line 91: 2.  **Semantic Rigidity:** Construct the DOM using precise semantic tags (`<data>`, `<samp>`, `<kbd>`, `<output>`, `<dl>`) to accurately reflect the technical nature of the telemetry.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/interaction-design.md:\n  Line 13: - Implementing smooth page and component transitions\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/pseudo-elements.md:\n  Line 6:   author: raphael-salaja\n\n  Line 316: components/button/styles.module.css:12 - [pseudo-content-required] ::before missing content property\n\n  Line 317: components/lightbox/index.tsx:45 - [transition-over-js-library] Using motion layoutId instead of View Transitions API\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/optimize.md:\n  Line 54: - Code splitting (route-based, component-based)\n\n  Line 58: - Use dynamic imports for large components\n\n  Line 61: // Lazy load heavy component\n\n  Line 163: - Use `memo()` for expensive components\n\n  Line 174: - Lazy load routes and components\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md:\n  Line 3: description: Design engineering principles for making interfaces feel polished. Use when building UI components, reviewing frontend code, implementing animations, hover states, shadows, borders, typography, micro-interactions, enter/exit animations, or any visual detail work. Triggers on UI polish, design details, \"make it feel better\", \"feels off\", stagger animations, border radius, optical alignment, font smoothing, tabular numbers, image outlines, box shadows.\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"DESIGN.md|Style Reference|extract|author|stitch|tokens|component|documentation|verbatim|PRODUCT.md|semantic","time":{"start":1782489125904,"end":1782489125915}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07938b3e991fec89016a3ea025a0d88190b8269885207b441c"}},"id":"prt_f04a1940e001ai6A9aVxZvHRD2","sessionID":"ses_0fb69c455ffeP1OgZTdo3RBP1U","messageID":"msg_f04a141e6001ZNyHc5sl0xmpOy"}}
